# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: genetics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The study of abiogenesis aims to determine how pre-life chemical reactions gave rise to life under conditions strikingly different from those on Earth today.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] It uses tools from biology and chemistry, attempting a synthesis of many sciences.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Life functions through the chemistry of carbon and water, and builds on four chemical families: lipids for cell membranes, carbohydrates such as sugars, amino acids for protein metabolism, and the nucleic acids DNA and RNA for heredity.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] A theory of abiogenesis must explain the origins and interactions of these classes of molecules.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Many approaches investigate how self-replicating molecules came into existence.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Researchers think that life descends from an RNA world, although other self-replicating and self-catalyzing molecules may have preceded RNA.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Other approaches ("metabolism-first" hypotheses) focus on how catalysis on the early Earth might have provided the precursor molecules for self-replication.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The 1952 Miller–Urey experiment demonstrated that amino acids can be synthesized from inorganic compounds under conditions like early Earth's.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Subsequently, amino acids have been found in meteorites, comets, asteroids, and star-forming regions of space.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] While the last universal common ancestor of all modern organisms (LUCA) existed millions of years after the origin of life, its study can guide research into early universal characteristics.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] A genomics approach has sought to characterize LUCA by identifying the genes shared by Archaea and Bacteria, major branches of life.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] It appears there are 60 proteins common to all life and 355 prokaryotic genes that trace to LUCA; their functions imply that LUCA was anaerobic with the Wood–Ljungdahl pathway, deriving energy by chemiosmosis, and used DNA, the genetic code, and ribosomes.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Earlier cells might have had a leaky membrane and been powered by a naturally occurring proton gradient near a deep-sea white smoker hydrothermal vent; or, life may have originated inside the continental crust or in water at Earth's surface.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth is the only place known to harbor life, astrobiologists assume that life exists and came into being by similar processes on other planets.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Geochemical and fossil evidence informs most studies.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The Earth was formed at 4.54 Gya, and the earliest evidence of life on Earth dates from 3.8 Gya from Western Australia.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Fossil micro-organisms may have lived in hydrothermal vent precipitates from Quebec, soon after ocean formation during the Hadean, so the process appears to have been relatively rapid in terms of geological time.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Life consists of reproduction with (heritable) variations.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] That in turn implies a suite of cellular machinery including messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Those proteins included enzymes to operate its anaerobic respiration via the Wood–Ljungdahl metabolic pathway, and a DNA polymerase to replicate its genetic material.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The challenge for origin of life researchers is to explain how such a complex and tightly interlinked system could develop by evolutionary steps, as at first sight all its parts are necessary to enable it to function.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] For example, a cell, whether the LUCA or in a modern organism, copies its DNA with the DNA polymerase enzyme, which is itself produced by translating the DNA polymerase gene in the DNA.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Neither the enzyme nor the DNA can be produced without the other.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The evolutionary process could have started with molecular self-replication, self-assembly such as of cell membranes, and autocatalysis via RNA ribozymes in an RNA world environment.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The transition of non-life to life has not been observed experimentally.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Some scientists see both life and the origin of life as aspects of the same process.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The preconditions to the development of a living cell like the LUCA are known, though disputed in detail: a habitable world is formed with a supply of minerals and liquid water and sources of free energy inflows such as our Sun and geothermal heat.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic synthesis creates a range of simple organic compounds, which are assembled into polymers such as proteins and RNA.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] On the other side, the process after the LUCA is readily understood: biological evolution caused the development of a wide range of species with varied forms and biochemical capabilities.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] However, the derivation of the LUCA from simple components is far from understood.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Although Earth remains the only place where life is known, the science of astrobiology seeks evidence of life on other planets.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The advent of such polymers was most likely a critical step in prebiotic chemical evolution.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Those polymers derived, in turn, from simple organic compounds such as nucleobases, amino acids, and sugars, likely formed by reactions in the environment.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] A successful theory of the origin of life must explain how all these chemicals came into being.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] One ancient view of the origin of life, from Aristotle until the 19th century, was of spontaneous generation.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] This held that "lower" animals such as insects were generated by decaying organic substances, and that life arose by chance.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] This was questioned from the 17th century, in works like Thomas Browne's *Pseudodoxia Epidemica*.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] In 1665, Robert Hooke published the first drawings of a microorganism.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] In 1676, Antonie van Leeuwenhoek drew and described microorganisms, probably protozoa and bacteria.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Van Leeuwenhoek disagreed with spontaneous generation, and by the 1680s convinced himself, using experiments ranging from sealed and open meat incubation and the close study of insect reproduction, that the theory was incorrect.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] In 1668 Francesco Redi showed that no maggots appeared in meat when flies were prevented from laying eggs.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] By the middle of the 19th century, spontaneous generation was considered disproven.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Dating back to Anaxagoras in the 5th century BC, panspermia is the idea that life originated elsewhere in the universe and came to Earth.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The modern version of panspermia holds that life may have been distributed to Earth by meteoroids, asteroids, comets or planetoids.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] This shifts the origin of life to another heavenly body.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The advantage is that life is not required to have formed on each planet it occurs on, but in a more limited set of locations, and then spread about the galaxy to other star systems.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] There is some interest in the possibility that life originated on Mars and later transferred to Earth.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The idea that life originated from non-living matter in slow stages appeared in Herbert Spencer's 1864–1867 book *Principles of Biology*, and in William Turner Thiselton-Dyer's 1879 paper "On spontaneous generation and evolution".
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane in 1929 proposed that the earliest cells slowly self-organized from a primordial soup, the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Haldane suggested that the Earth's prebiotic oceans consisted of a "hot dilute soup" in which organic compounds could have formed.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Bernal showed that such mechanisms could form most of the necessary molecules for life from inorganic precursors.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] In 1967, he suggested three "stages": the origin of biological monomers; the origin of biological polymers; and the evolution from molecules to cells.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] In 1952, Stanley Miller and Harold Urey carried out a chemical experiment to demonstrate how organic molecules could have formed spontaneously from inorganic precursors under prebiotic conditions like those posited by the Oparin–Haldane hypothesis.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] It passed an electric current through a highly reducing (lacking oxygen) mixture of gases—methane, ammonia, and hydrogen, with water vapor—to form organic monomers such as amino acids.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The addition of iron and carbonate minerals, present in early oceans, produces a diverse array of amino acids.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Later work has focused on two other potential reducing environments: outer space and deep-sea hydrothermal vents.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after the Big Bang, roughly 14 Gya, the only chemical elements present in the universe were hydrogen, helium, and lithium, the three lightest atoms in the periodic table.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] These elements gradually condensed into vast clouds of gas, which collapsed under gravity into rotating protostellar disks.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Gravitational accretion of material at the hot and dense centers of these disks formed the first stars by the fusion of hydrogen.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Early stars were massive and short-lived, producing all the heavier elements by stellar nucleosynthesis.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Such element formation proceeds to its most stable element Iron-56.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Heavier elements were formed during supernovas at the end of a star's lifecycle.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon, currently the fourth most abundant element in the universe, was formed mainly in white dwarf stars.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] As these stars reached the end of their lifecycles, they ejected heavier elements, including carbon and oxygen, throughout the universe.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] These allowed for the formation of rocky planets.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] According to the nebular hypothesis, the Solar System began to form 4.6 Gya with the gravitational collapse of part of a giant molecular cloud.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Most of the collapsing mass collected in the center, forming the Sun, while the rest flattened into a protoplanetary disk out of which the planets formed.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The age of the Earth is 4.54 Gya as found by radiometric dating of calcium-aluminium-rich inclusions in carbonaceous chrondrite meteorites, the oldest material in the Solar System.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Earth, during the Hadean eon (from its formation until 4.031 Gya,) was at first inhospitable to life.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] During its formation, the Earth lost much of its initial mass, and so lacked the gravity to hold molecular hydrogen and the bulk of the original inert gases.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Soon after initial accretion of Earth at 4.48 Gya, its collision with Theia, a hypothesised impactor, is thought to have created the ejected debris that eventually formed the Moon.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] This impact removed the Earth's primary atmosphere, leaving behind clouds of viscous silicates and carbon dioxide.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] This unstable atmosphere was short-lived, soon condensing to form the bulk silicate Earth, leaving behind an atmosphere largely consisting of water vapor, nitrogen, and carbon dioxide, with smaller amounts of carbon monoxide, hydrogen, and sulfur compounds.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The solution of carbon dioxide in water is thought to have made the seas slightly acidic, with a pH of about 5.5.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Condensation to form liquid oceans is theorised to have occurred as early as the Moon-forming impact.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] This scenario is supported by the dating of 4.404 Gya zircon crystals with high *δ*18O values from metamorphosed quartzite of Mount Narryer in Western Australia.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The Hadean atmosphere has been characterized as a "gigantic, productive outdoor chemical laboratory," similar to volcanic gases today which still support some abiotic chemistry.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Despite the likely increased volcanism from early plate tectonics, the Earth may have been a predominantly water world between 4.4 and 4.3 Gya.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] It is debated whether crust was exposed above this ocean.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Immediately after the Moon-forming impact, Earth likely had little if any continental crust, a turbulent atmosphere, and a hydrosphere subject to intense ultraviolet light from a T Tauri stage Sun.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] It was also affected by cosmic radiation, and continued asteroid and comet impacts.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The Late Heavy Bombardment hypothesis posits that a period of intense impact occurred at 4.1 to 3.8 Gya during the Hadean and early Archean eons.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Originally it was thought that the Late Heavy Bombardment was a single cataclysmic impact event occurring at 3.9 Gya; this would have had the potential to sterilize Earth by volatilizing liquid oceans and blocking sunlight needed for photosynthesis, delaying the earliest possible emergence of life.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] More recent research questioned the intensity of the Late Heavy Bombardment and its potential for sterilisation.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] If it was not one giant impact but a period of raised impact rate, it would have had much less destructive power.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The 3.9 Gya date arose from dating of Apollo mission sample returns collected mostly near the Imbrium Basin, biasing the age of recorded impacts.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Impact modelling of the lunar surface reveals that rather than a cataclysmic event at 3.9 Gya, multiple small-scale, short-lived periods of bombardment likely occurred.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Terrestrial data backs this idea by showing multiple periods of ejecta in the rock record both before and after the 3.9 Gya marker, suggesting that the early Earth was subject to continuous impacts with less impact on extinction.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from late impacts and the then high levels of ultraviolet radiation from the sun.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The available energy is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Based on evidence from the geologic record, life most likely emerged on Earth between 4.32 and 3.48 Gya.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] In 2017, the earliest physical evidence of life was reported to consist of microbialites in the Nuvvuagittuq Greenstone Belt of Northern Quebec, in banded iron formation rocks at least 3.77 and possibly as old as 4.32 Gya.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The micro-organisms could have lived within hydrothermal vent precipitates, soon after the 4.4 Gya formation of oceans during the Hadean.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The microbes resemble modern hydrothermal vent bacteria, supporting the view that abiogenesis began in such an environment.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Later research disputed this interpretation of the data, stating that the observations may be better explained by abiotic processes in silica-rich waters, "chemical gardens," circulating hydrothermal fluids, or volcanic ejecta.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Biogenic graphite has been found in 3.7 Gya metasedimentary rocks from southwestern Greenland and in microbial mat fossils from 3.49 Gya cherts in the Pilbara region of Western Australia.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Evidence of early life in rocks from Akilia Island, near the Isua supracrustal belt in southwestern Greenland, dating to 3.7 Gya, have shown biogenic carbon isotopes.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] In other parts of the Isua supracrustal belt, graphite inclusions trapped within garnet crystals are connected to the other elements of life: oxygen, nitrogen, and possibly phosphorus in the form of phosphate, providing further evidence for life 3.7 Gya.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] In the Pilbara region of Western Australia, compelling evidence of early life was found in pyrite-bearing sandstone in a fossilized beach, with rounded tubular cells that oxidized sulfur by photosynthesis in the absence of oxygen.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon isotope ratios on graphite inclusions from the Jack Hills zircons suggest that life could have existed on Earth from 4.1 Gya.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 study inferred LUCA's age as around 4.2 Gya (4.09–4.33 Gya) by analysing pre-LUCA gene duplicates, with calibration from fossil micro-organisms, much sooner after the origin of life than previously thought.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The Pilbara region of Western Australia contains the Dresser Formation with rocks 3.48 Gya, including layered structures called stromatolites.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Their modern counterparts are created by photosynthetic micro-organisms including cyanobacteria.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] These lie within undeformed hydrothermal-sedimentary strata; their texture indicates a biogenic origin.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Parts of the Dresser formation preserve hot springs on land, but other regions seem to have been shallow seas.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] A molecular clock analysis suggests the LUCA emerged prior to 3.9 Gya.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] All chemical elements derive from stellar nucleosynthesis except for hydrogen and some helium and lithium.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Basic chemical ingredients of life – the carbon-hydrogen molecule (CH), the carbon-hydrogen positive ion (CH+) and the carbon ion (C+) – can be produced by ultraviolet light from stars.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Complex molecules, including organic molecules, form naturally both in space and on planets.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] An organic compound is a chemical whose molecules contain carbon.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon is abundant in the Sun, stars, comets, and in the atmospheres of most planets of the Solar System.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds are relatively common in space, formed by "factories of complex molecular synthesis" which occur in molecular clouds and circumstellar envelopes, and chemically evolve after reactions are initiated mostly by ionizing radiation.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Purine and pyrimidine nucleobases including guanine, adenine, cytosine, uracil, and thymine, as well as sugars, have been found in meteorites.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] These could have provided the materials for DNA and RNA to form on the early Earth.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The amino acid glycine was found in material ejected from comet Wild 2; it had earlier been detected in meteorites.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Comets are encrusted with dark material, thought to be a tar-like organic substance formed from simple carbon compounds under ionizing radiation.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] A rain of material from comets could have brought such complex organic molecules to Earth.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] During the Late Heavy Bombardment, meteorites may have delivered up to five million tons of organic prebiotic elements to Earth per year.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Currently 40,000 tons of cosmic dust falls to Earth each year.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons (PAH) are the most common and abundant polyatomic molecules in the observable universe, and are a major store of carbon.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] They seem to have formed shortly after the Big Bang, and are associated with new stars and exoplanets.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] They are a likely constituent of Earth's primordial sea.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs have been detected in nebulae, and in the interstellar medium, in comets, and in meteorites.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] A star, HH 46-IR, resembling the sun early in its life, is surrounded by a disk of material which contains molecules including cyanide compounds, hydrocarbons, and carbon monoxide.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] PAHs in the interstellar medium can be transformed through hydrogenation, oxygenation, and hydroxylation to more complex organic compounds used in living cells.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Organic compounds introduced on Earth by interstellar dust particles can help to form complex molecules, thanks to their peculiar surface-catalytic activities.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA component uracil and related molecules, including xanthine, in the Murchison meteorite were likely formed extraterrestrially, as suggested by studies of 12C/13C isotopic ratios.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] NASA studies of meteorites suggest that all four DNA nucleobases (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) have been formed in outer space.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The cosmic dust permeating the universe contains complex organics ("amorphous organic solids with a mixed aromatic–aliphatic structure") that could be created rapidly by stars.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Glycolaldehyde, a sugar molecule and RNA precursor, has been detected in regions of space including around protostars and on meteorites.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] As early as the 1860s, experiments demonstrated that biologically relevant molecules can be produced from interaction of simple carbon sources with abundant inorganic catalysts.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The spontaneous formation of complex polymers from abiotically generated monomers under the conditions posited by the "soup" theory is not straightforward.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Besides the necessary basic organic monomers, compounds that would have prohibited the formation of polymers were also formed in high concentration during the Miller–Urey experiment and Joan Oró experiments.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Biology uses essentially 20 amino acids for its coded protein enzymes, representing a very small subset of the structurally possible products.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Since life tends to use whatever is available, an explanation is needed for why the set used is so small.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide is attractive as a medium that potentially provided a source of amino acid derivatives from simple aldehyde and nitrile feedstocks.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Alexander Butlerov showed in 1861 that the formose reaction created sugars including tetroses, pentoses, and hexoses when formaldehyde is heated under basic conditions with divalent metal ions like calcium.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Breslow proposed that the reaction was autocatalytic in 1959.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Nucleobases, such as guanine and adenine, can be synthesized from simple carbon and nitrogen sources, such as hydrogen cyanide (HCN) and ammonia.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] On early Earth, HCN was likely supplied via photochemical production in a transient, highly reducing atmosphere after major impacts.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Formamide, from the reaction of water and HCN, produces all four ribonucleotides when warmed with terrestrial minerals.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] HCN can contribute to chemical processes such as the synthesis of the amino acid glycine.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] DNA and RNA components including uracil, cytosine and thymine can be synthesized under outer space conditions, using starting chemicals such as pyrimidine from meteorites.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Pyrimidine may have formed in red giant stars, interstellar dust, or gas clouds, or on Earth via precursors such as cyanoacetylene following asteroid impacts.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] All four RNA-bases may be synthesized from formamide in high-energy density events like extraterrestrial impacts.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Several ribonucleotides for RNA formation have been synthesized in a laboratory environment which replicates prebiotic conditions via autocatalytic formose reaction.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Other pathways for synthesizing bases from inorganic materials have been reported.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Freezing temperatures assist the synthesis of purines, by concentrating key precursors such as HCN.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] However, while adenine and guanine require freezing conditions, cytosine and uracil may require boiling temperatures.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Seven amino acids and eleven types of nucleobases formed in ice when ammonia and cyanide were left in a freezer for 25 years.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] S-triazines (alternative nucleobases), pyrimidines including cytosine and uracil, and adenine can be synthesized by subjecting a urea solution to freeze-thaw cycles under a reductive atmosphere with spark discharges.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] These low-temperature reactions proceed rapidly due to eutectic freezing, which crowds impurities in microscopic pockets of liquid within the ice.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Prebiotic peptide synthesis could have occurred by several routes.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Some center on high temperature/concentration conditions in which condensation becomes energetically favorable, while others use plausible prebiotic condensing agents.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Experimental evidence for the formation of peptides in uniquely concentrated environments is bolstered by work suggesting that wet-dry cycles and the presence of specific salts can greatly increase spontaneous condensation of glycine into poly-glycine chains.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Other work suggests that while mineral surfaces, such as those of pyrite, calcite, and rutile catalyze peptide condensation, they also catalyze their hydrolysis.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The authors suggest that additional chemical activation or coupling would be necessary to produce peptides at sufficient concentrations.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Thus, mineral surface catalysis, while important, is not sufficient alone for peptide synthesis.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Many prebiotically plausible condensing/activating agents have been identified, including the following: cyanamide, dicyanamide, dicyandiamide, diaminomaleonitrile, urea, trimetaphosphate, NaCl, CuCl2, (Ni,Fe)S, CO, carbonyl sulfide (COS), carbon disulfide (CS2), SO2, and diammonium phosphate (DAP).
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] A 2024 experiment used a sapphire substrate with a web of thin cracks under a heat flow, mimicking deep-ocean vents, to concentrate prebiotically-relevant building blocks from a dilute mixture by up to three orders of magnitude.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] This could help to create biopolymers such as peptides.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] A similar role has been suggested for clays, though this speculation has not been supported through experimental evidence.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The prebiotic synthesis of peptides from simpler molecules such as CO, NH3 and C, skipping the step of amino acid formation, is also very efficient.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The largest unanswered question in evolution is how simple protocells first arose and differed in reproductive contribution to the following generation, thus initiating evolution.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The lipid world theory postulates that the first self-replicating object was lipid-like.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Phospholipids form lipid bilayers (as in cell membranes) in water while under agitation.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] These molecules were not present on early Earth, but other membrane-forming amphiphilic long-chain molecules were.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] These bodies may expand by insertion of additional lipids, and may spontaneously split into two offspring of similar size and composition.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Lipid bodies may have provided sheltering envelopes for information storage, allowing the evolution of information-storing polymers like RNA.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Only one or two types of vesicle-forming amphiphiles have been studied.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Such site/compound pairs are transmissible to the daughter vesicles, leading to the emergence of distinct lineages of vesicles, subject to natural selection.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] A protocell is a self-organized, self-ordered, spherical collection of lipids proposed as a stepping-stone to life, that is capable of evolving.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembled vesicles are essential components of primitive cells.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The theory of classical irreversible thermodynamics treats self-assembly under a generalized chemical potential within the framework of dissipative systems.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The second law of thermodynamics requires that overall entropy increases, yet life is distinguished by its great degree of organization.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Therefore, a boundary is needed to separate ordered life processes from chaotic non-living matter.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] A functional protocell, which must exhibit Darwinian evolution, has not yet been achieved in a laboratory setting.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Szostak suggest that elementary protocells can give rise to primitive forms of differential reproduction, competition, and energy storage.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Competition for membrane molecules would favor stabilized membranes, suggesting a selective advantage for cross-linked fatty acids and even modern phospholipids.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Such micro-encapsulation would allow for metabolism within the membrane and the exchange of small molecules, while retaining large biomolecules inside.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Such a membrane is needed for a cell to create its own electrochemical gradient.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Vesicles can undergo an evolutionary process under pressure cycling conditions.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Simulating the systemic environment in tectonic fault zones within the Earth's crust, pressure cycling forms vesicles periodically, as well as random peptide chains which are selected for ability to integrate into the vesicle membrane.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Further selection of vesicles for stability could lead to functional peptide structures, increasing vesicle survival rate.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Life requires a loss of entropy, or disorder, as molecules organize themselves into living matter.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] At the same time, the emergence of life is associated with the formation of structures beyond a certain threshold of complexity.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Multiple sources of energy were available for chemical reactions on the early Earth.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Heat from geothermal processes is a standard energy source for chemistry.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Other examples include sunlight, lightning, atmospheric entries of micro-meteorites, and implosion of bubbles in sea and ocean waves.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] This has been confirmed by experiments and simulations.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Unfavorable reactions can be driven by highly favorable ones, as in the case of iron-sulfur chemistry.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] For example, this was probably important for carbon fixation.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Carbon fixation by reaction of CO2 with H2S via iron-sulfur chemistry is favorable, and occurs at neutral pH and 100 °C.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Iron-sulfur surfaces, which are abundant near hydrothermal vents, can drive the production of small amounts of amino acids and other biomolecules.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] In 1961, Peter Mitchell proposed chemiosmosis as a cell's primary system of energy conversion.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism, now ubiquitous in living cells, powers energy conversion in micro-organisms and in the mitochondria of eukaryotes, making it a likely candidate for early life.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Mitochondria produce adenosine triphosphate (ATP), the energy currency of the cell used to drive cellular processes such as chemical syntheses.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The mechanism of ATP synthesis involves a closed membrane in which the ATP synthase enzyme is embedded.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The energy required to release strongly bound ATP has its origin in protons that move across the membrane.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] In modern cells, those proton movements are caused by the pumping of ions across the membrane, maintaining an electrochemical gradient.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] However, as yet, the hypothesis is untested.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The RNA world hypothesis describes an early Earth with self-replicating and catalytic RNA but no DNA or proteins.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] It was proposed in 1962 by Alexander Rich; the term was coined by Walter Gilbert in 1986.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Many researchers concur that an RNA world must have preceded modern DNA-based life.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] However, it may not have been the first to exist.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] There may have been over 30 chemical events between pre-RNA world to near-LUCA, just involving RNA.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] RNA is central to the translation process.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Small RNAs can catalyze all the chemical groups and information transfers required for life.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] RNA both expresses and maintains genetic information in modern organisms; its components are easily synthesized under early Earth conditions.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The structure of the ribosome has been called the "smoking gun", with a central core of RNA and no amino acid side chains within 18 Å of the active site that catalyzes peptide bond formation.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] RNA replicase can both code and catalyse further RNA replication, i.e. it is autocatalytic.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Some catalytic RNAs can link smaller RNA sequences together, enabling self-replication.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Natural selection would then favor the proliferation of such autocatalytic sets.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Self-assembly of RNA may occur spontaneously in hydrothermal vents.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] A preliminary form of tRNA could have assembled into a replicator molecule.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] When this began to replicate, it may have had all three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation, and differential reproduction.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Its fitness would have depended on its ability to adapt, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and resource availability.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Starting with the work of Carl Woese from 1977, genomics studies have placed the last universal common ancestor (LUCA) of all modern life-forms between Bacteria and a clade formed by Archaea and Eukaryota in the phylogenetic tree of life.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] A minority of studies have placed the LUCA in Bacteria, proposing that Archaea and Eukaryota are evolutionarily derived from within Eubacteria; Thomas Cavalier-Smith suggested in 2006 that the phenotypically diverse bacterial phylum Chloroflexota contained the LUCA.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] In 2016, a set of 355 genes likely present in the LUCA was identified.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] A total of 6.1 million prokaryotic genes from Bacteria and Archaea were sequenced, identifying 355 protein clusters from among 286,514 protein clusters that were probably common to the LUCA.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The results suggest that the LUCA was anaerobic with a Wood–Ljungdahl (reductive Acetyl-CoA) pathway, nitrogen- and carbon-fixing, thermophilic.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Its cofactors suggest dependence upon an environment rich in hydrogen, carbon dioxide, iron, and transition metals.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Its genetic material was probably DNA, requiring the 4-nucleotide genetic code, messenger RNA, transfer RNA, and ribosomes to translate the code into proteins such as enzymes.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] LUCA likely inhabited an anaerobic hydrothermal vent setting in a geochemically active environment.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] It was evidently already a complex organism, and must have had precursors; it was not the first living thing.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] The physiology of LUCA has been in dispute.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Previous research identified 60 proteins common to all life.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p01] Metabolic reactions inferred in LUCA are the incomplete reverse Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, the pentose phosphate pathway, glycolysis, reductive amination, and transamination.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] A variety of geologic and environmental settings have been proposed for an origin of life.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] These theories are often in competition with one another as there are many views of prebiotic compound availability, geophysical setting, and early life characteristics.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] The first organism on Earth likely differed from LUCA.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Between the first appearance of life and where all modern phylogenies began branching, an unknown amount of time passed, with unknown gene transfers, extinctions, and adaptation to environmental niches.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Modern phylogenies provide more genetic evidence about LUCA than about its precursors.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Early micro-fossils may have come from a hot world of gases such as methane, ammonia, carbon dioxide, and hydrogen sulfide, toxic to much current life.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Analysis of the tree of life places thermophilic and hyperthermophilic bacteria and archaea closest to the root, suggesting that life may have evolved in a hot environment.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] The deep sea or alkaline hydrothermal vent theory posits that life began at submarine hydrothermal vents.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] William Martin and Michael Russell have suggested that this could have been in metal-sulphide-walled compartments acting as precursors for cell walls.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] These form where hydrogen-rich fluids emerge from below the sea floor, as a result of serpentinization of ultra-mafic olivine with seawater and a pH interface with carbon dioxide-rich ocean water.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] The vents form a sustained chemical energy source derived from redox reactions, in which electron donors (molecular hydrogen) react with electron acceptors (carbon dioxide); see iron–sulfur world theory.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Russell demonstrated that alkaline vents create an abiogenic proton motive force chemiosmotic gradient, ideal for abiogenesis.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Their microscopic compartments "provide a natural means of concentrating organic molecules," composed of iron-sulfur minerals such as mackinawite, endowed these mineral cells with the catalytic properties envisaged by Günter Wächtershäuser.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Electrostatic force caused by electrical potential gradient—cations like protons H+ diffuse down the electrical potential, anions in the opposite direction.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] These two gradients together can be expressed as an electrochemical gradient, providing energy for abiogenic synthesis.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] The proton motive force measures the potential energy stored as proton and voltage gradients across a membrane (differences in proton concentration and electrical potential).
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] In 2016, Martin suggested that the LUCA "may have depended heavily on the geothermal energy of the vent to survive".
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] That same year, RNA was produced in synthetic alkaline hydrothermal chimneys simulating deep-sea vents.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Researchers were able to generate RNA oligomers of up to 4 units in length.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] This RNA was synthesized using activated ribonucleotides.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Additionally, these RNA oligomers could only be synthesized under certain conditions.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Pores at deep sea hydrothermal vents are suggested to have been occupied by membrane-bound compartments which promoted biochemical reactions.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Metabolic intermediates in the Krebs cycle, gluconeogenesis, amino acid bio-synthetic pathways, glycolysis, the pentose phosphate pathway, and including sugars like ribose, and lipid precursors can occur non-enzymatically at conditions relevant to deep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] If the deep marine hydrothermal setting was the site, then life could have arisen as early as 4.0–4.2 Gya.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] If life evolved in the ocean at depths of more than ten meters, it would have been shielded both from impacts and the then high levels of solar ultraviolet radiation.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] The available energy in hydrothermal vents is maximized at 100–150 °C, the temperatures at which hyperthermophilic bacteria and thermoacidophilic archaea live.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Hyperthermophily could have been a result of convergent evolution in bacteria and archaea; a mesophilic environment has been called more likely.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Production of prebiotic organic compounds at hydrothermal vents is estimated to be 108 kg/yr.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Key prebiotic compounds, such as methane are in far lower concentrations at vents than in a Miller-Urey Experiment environment.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Some organic compounds are now understood to have been formed by other geological processes and inherited by vents.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Methane, for example, more likely comes from leached fluid inclusions formed deeper in oceanic crust from magmatic carbon.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Vents do not concentrate prebiotic materials, due to strong dilution by seawater.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] This open system cycles compounds through vent minerals, leaving little residence time to accumulate.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] All modern cells rely on phosphates for nucleotide backbone and potassium for protein formation, making it likely that the first life forms shared these functions.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] These elements were not available in high quantities in the Archaean oceans.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] However, phosphate can be concentrated in lakes, as in the modern Last Chance Lake.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Submarine hydrothermal vents are not conducive to condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] An older argument was that key polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation, which supposedly would not happen in saltwater.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] However, while salinity inhibits vesicle formation from low-diversity mixtures of fatty acids, vesicle formation from a broader, more realistic mix of fatty-acid and 1-alkanol species is more resilient.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] No studies have been able to experimentally demonstrate synthesis of sugars, amino acids, nucleases, nucleosides, nucleotides, or membrane-forming fatty acids under plausible vent conditions.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Surface bodies of water provide environments that dry out and rewet.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Wet-dry cycles concentrate prebiotic compounds and enable condensation reactions to polymerise macromolecules.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, lakes and ponds receive detrital input from weathering of continental apatite-containing rocks, the most common source of phosphates.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] The amount of exposed continental crust in the Hadean is unknown, but models of early ocean depths and rates of ocean island and continental crust growth make it plausible that there was exposed land.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Another line of evidence for a surface start to life is the requirement for Ultraviolet radiation (UV) for organism function.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] UV is necessary for the formation of the U+C nucleotide base pair by partial hydrolysis and nucleobase loss.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Simultaneously, UV can be harmful and sterilising to life, especially for simple early lifeforms with little ability to repair radiation damage.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Radiation levels from a young Sun were likely greater, and, with no ozone layer, harmful shortwave UV rays would reach the surface of Earth.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] For life to begin, a shielded environment with influx from UV-exposed sources is necessary to both benefit and protect from UV.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Shielding under ice, liquid water, mineral surfaces (e.g. clay) or regolith is possible in a range of surface water settings.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Most branching phylogenies are thermophilic or hyperthermophilic, making it possible that LUCA and preceding lifeforms were similarly thermophilic.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs are formed from the heating of groundwater by geothermal activity.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] This intersection allows for influxes of material from deep penetrating waters and from surface runoff that transports eroded continental sediments.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Interconnected groundwater systems create a mechanism for distribution of life to wider area.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Mulkidjanian and co-authors argue that marine environments did not provide the ionic balance and composition universally found in cells, or the ions required by essential proteins and ribozymes, especially with respect to high K+/Na+ ratio, Mn2+, Zn2+ and phosphate concentrations.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] They argue that the only environments that do this are hot springs similar to ones at Kamchatka.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] The hypothesized pre-biotic environments are similar to hydrothermal vents, with additional components that help explain peculiarities of the LUCA.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] A phylogenomic and geochemical analysis of proteins plausibly traced to the LUCA shows that the ionic composition of its intracellular fluid is identical to that of hot springs.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] The LUCA likely was dependent upon synthesized organic matter for its growth.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments show that RNA-like polymers can be synthesized in wet-dry cycling and UV light exposure.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] These polymers were encapsulated in vesicles after condensation.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Potential sources of organics at hot springs might have been transported by interplanetary dust particles, extraterrestrial projectiles, or atmospheric or geochemical synthesis.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Hot springs could have been abundant in volcanic landmasses during the Hadean.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] A mesophilic start in surface bodies of waters hypothesis has evolved from Darwin's concept of a 'warm little pond' and the Oparin-Haldane hypothesis.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Freshwater bodies under temperate climates can accumulate prebiotic materials while providing suitable environmental conditions conducive to simple life forms.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Atmospheric reconstructions from geochemical proxies and models suggest that sufficient greenhouse gases were present to maintain surface temperatures between 0–40 °C.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] If so, the temperature was suitable for life to begin.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Evidence for mesophily from biomolecular studies includes Galtier's G+C nucleotide thermometer.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] G+C are more abundant in thermophiles due to the added stability of an additional hydrogen bond not present between A+T nucleotides. rRNA sequencing of modern lifeforms shows that LUCA's reconstructed G+C content was likely representative of moderate temperatures.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] The diversity of thermophiles today could be a product of convergent evolution and horizontal gene transfer rather than an inherited trait from LUCA.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] The reverse gyrase topoisomerase is found exclusively in thermophiles and hyperthermophiles, as it allows for coiling of DNA.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] This enzyme requires the complex molecule ATP to function.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] If an origin of life is hypothesised to involve a simple organism that had not yet evolved a membrane, let alone ATP, this would make the existence of reverse gyrase improbable.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Moreover, phylogenetic studies show that reverse gyrase originated in archaea, and transferred to bacteria by horizontal gene transfer, implying it was not present in the LUCA.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Cold-start theories presuppose large ice-covered regions.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Stellar evolution models predict that the Sun's luminosity was ≈25% weaker than it is today.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Fuelner states that although this significant decrease in solar energy would have formed an icy planet, there is strong evidence for the presence of liquid water, possibly driven by a greenhouse effect.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] This would mean an early Earth with both liquid oceans and icy poles.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Ice melts that form from ice sheets or glacier melts create freshwater pools, another niche capable of wet-dry cycles.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] While surface pools would be exposed to intense UV radiation, bodies of water within and under ice would be shielded, while remaining connected to exposed areas through ice cracks.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Impact melting would allow freshwater and meteoritic input, creating prebiotic components.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Near-seawater levels of sodium chloride destabilize fatty acid membrane self-assembly, making freshwater settings appealing for early membranous life.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Icy environments would trade the faster reaction rates that occur in warm environments for increased stability and accumulation of larger polymers.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Experiments simulating Europa-like conditions of ≈20 °C have synthesised amino acids and adenine, showing that Miller-Urey type syntheses can occur at low temperatures.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] In an RNA world, the ribozyme would have had even more functions than in a later DNA-RNA-protein-world.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] For RNA to function, it must be able to fold, a process hindered by temperatures above 30 °C.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] While RNA folding in psychrophilic organisms is slower, so is hydrolysis, so folding is more successful.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Shorter nucleotides would not suffer from higher temperatures.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] The continental crust, with tectonic fault zones could present a stable and well-protected environment for long-term prebiotic evolution.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Inside these systems of cracks and cavities, water and carbon dioxide present the bulk solvents.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Their phase state could vary between liquid, gaseous and supercritical, depending on pressure and temperature.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] When forming two separate phases, the system provides optimal conditions for phase transfer reactions.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Concurrently, the contents of the tectonic fault zones are supplied with inorganic educts (e.g. carbon monoxide, hydrogen, ammonia, hydrogen cyanide, nitrogen, and phosphate) and simple organic molecules (e.g. amino acids, long-chain amines, fatty acids, long-chain aldehydes).
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Part of the tectonic fault zones is at a depth of around 1000 m.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] For carbon dioxide, it provides temperature and pressure conditions near the phase transition point between the supercritical and the gaseous state.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] This allows lipophilic organic molecules that dissolve well in supercritical CO2 to accumulate, leading to local precipitation.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Periodic pressure variations such as caused by geysers or tidal influences result in periodic phase transitions, keeping the local reaction environment in a constant non-equilibrium state.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] In presence of amphiphilic compounds (such as the long chain amines and fatty acids), subsequent generations of vesicles are formed that are selected for their stability.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Homochirality is the uniformity of materials composed of chiral (non-mirror-symmetric) units.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Living organisms use molecules with the same chirality: with almost no exceptions, amino acids are left-handed while nucleotides and sugars are right-handed.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Chiral molecules can be synthesized, but in the absence of a chiral source or a chiral catalyst, they are formed in a 50/50 (racemic) mixture of both forms.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Non-racemic mixtures can arise from racemic materials by asymmetric physical laws such as the electroweak interaction, or in asymmetric environments, such as those in which molecules are exposed to circularly polarized light of a given handedness.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] It has been hypothesized that the solar nebula was such an environment, exposed to circularly-polarized radiation from an external source before or during the epoch of planet formation.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] This proposal is consistent with the finding that some amino acids delivered to Earth in meteorites exhibit a chiral asymmetry of the same sign as terrestrial life.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] Once established, a chirality imbalance may influence subsequent chemical evolution.
[src:genetics/abiogenesis-p02] A small bias in the population can be amplified by asymmetric autocatalysis, as in the Soai reaction, where a chiral molecule catalyzes its own production.
[src:genetics/acentric-fragment] An **acentric fragment** is a segment of a chromosome that lacks a centromere.
[src:genetics/acentric-fragment] Because the centromere is the point of attachment for the mitotic apparatus, acentric fragments are not evenly distributed to the daughter cells in cell division (mitosis and meiosis).
[src:genetics/acentric-fragment] As a result, one of the daughters will lack the acentric fragment.
[src:genetics/acentric-fragment] Lack of the acentric fragment in one of the daughter cells may have deleterious consequences, depending on the function of the DNA in this region of the chromosome.
[src:genetics/acentric-fragment] In the case of a haploid organism or a gamete, it will be fatal to one of the daughter cells if essential DNA is contained in the lost DNA segment.
[src:genetics/acentric-fragment] In the case of a diploid organism, the daughter cell lacking the acentric fragment will show expression of any recessive genes found in the homologous chromosome.
[src:genetics/acentric-fragment] Developmental geneticists look for cells and cell lineages lacking unpaired chromosome segments produced this way as a means of identifying essential genes for specific functions.
[src:genetics/acentric-fragment] Acentric fragments are commonly generated by chromosome-breaking events, such as irradiation.
[src:genetics/acentric-fragment] Such acentric fragments are unequally distributed between the daughter cells after cell division.
[src:genetics/acentric-fragment] Acentric fragments can also be produced when an inverted segment is present in one member of a chromosome pair.
[src:genetics/acentric-fragment] In that case, a crossover event will result in one chromosome with two centromeres and an acentric fragment.
[src:genetics/acentric-fragment] The acentric fragment will be lost as explained above, and chromosomes with two centromeres will break unevenly during mitosis, resulting in one daughter lacking essential genes.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] In the 1930s–1950s Joachim Hämmerling conducted experiments in which he demonstrated *Acetabularia*'s genetic information is contained in the nucleus.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] This was the first demonstration that genes are encoded by DNA in eukaryotes; earlier studies by Oswald Avery and others had shown that this was true for prokaryotes.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] The name, *Acetabularia*, derives from the Latin word *acetabulum*, a broad, shallow cup used for dipping bread; the upturned cap of *Acetabularia* resembles such a cup.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] For this reason, it is also sometimes called **mermaid's wineglass**.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] In the 19th century, the same designation *Acetabularia* was proposed by George Edward Massee for a genus of fungi (now *Cyphellopus*), but this usage is obsolete and considered invalid as the algal name takes precedence.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] Each *Acetabularia* cell is composed of three segments: the "foot" or basal segment which contains the nucleus, the "stalk", and the "cap".
[src:genetics/acetabularia] Hämmerling exchanged caps between individuals from two species, *A. mediterranea* and *A. crenulata*.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] *A. mediterranea* has a smooth, disc-shaped cap, while *A. crenulata* has a branched, flower-like cap.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] After the exchange, each transplanted cap gradually changed from its original form to the form typical for the species of the base it was now attached to.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] This showed that the nucleus controlled the form of the cap.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] In another experiment, Hämmerling inserted a nucleus from one species of *Acetabularia* into an intact *Acetabularia* of a different species.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] The *Acetabularia* then produced a hybrid cap with characteristics of both species.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] This showed that both nuclei influenced the form of the cap.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] Hammerling's results showed that the nucleus of a cell contains the genetic information that directs cellular development.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] Although a single cell, *Acetabularia* exhibits a remarkably complex shape and has therefore long been a model organism for studying gene expression and morphogenesis.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] It seems to transport messenger RNA molecules (in an inactive riboprotein form) from the nucleus to its apical tips, where they are translated into proteins.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] These molecules may be activated by proteolysis of their protein carrier molecules, but this has not been verified as yet.
[src:genetics/acetabularia] In addition to its gradient in specific mRNA molecules, *Acetabularia* exhibits concentration gradients in several types of molecules, such as ascorbic acid.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The **centromere** links a pair of sister chromatids together during cell division.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] This constricted region of chromosome connects the sister chromatids, creating a short arm (p) and a long arm (q) on the chromatids.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] During mitosis, spindle fibers attach to the centromere via the kinetochore.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] There are, broadly speaking, two types of centromeres.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] "Point centromeres" bind to specific proteins that recognize particular DNA sequences with high efficiency.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Any piece of DNA with the point centromere DNA sequence on it will typically form a centromere if present in the appropriate species.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The best characterized point centromeres are those of the budding yeast, *Saccharomyces cerevisiae*.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] "Regional centromeres" is the term coined to describe most centromeres, which typically form on regions of preferred DNA sequence, but which can form on other DNA sequences as well.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The signal for formation of a regional centromere appears to be epigenetic.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Most organisms, ranging from the fission yeast *Schizosaccharomyces pombe* to humans, have regional centromeres.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Regarding mitotic chromosome structure, centromeres represent a constricted region of the chromosome (often referred to as the primary constriction) where two identical sister chromatids are most closely in contact.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] When cells enter mitosis, the sister chromatids (the two copies of each chromosomal DNA molecule resulting from DNA replication in chromatin form) are linked along their length by the action of the cohesin complex.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In humans, centromere positions define the chromosomal karyotype, in which each chromosome has two arms, *p* (the shorter of the two) and *q* (the longer).
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The short arm 'p' is reportedly named for the French word "petit" meaning 'small'.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The position of the centromere relative to any particular linear chromosome is used to classify chromosomes as metacentric, submetacentric, acrocentric, telocentric, or holocentric.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Metacentric means that the centromere is positioned midway between the chromosome ends, resulting in the arms being approximately equal in length.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Submetacentric means that the centromere is positioned below the middle, with one chromosome arm shorter than the other, often resulting in an L shape.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] An acrocentric chromosome's centromere is situated so that one of the chromosome arms is much shorter than the other.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The "acro-" in acrocentric refers to the Greek word for "peak." The human genome has six acrocentric chromosomes, including five autosomal chromosomes (13, 14, 15, 21, 22) and the Y chromosome.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Short acrocentric p-arms contain little genetic material and can be translocated without significant harm, as in a balanced Robertsonian translocation.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In addition to some protein coding genes, human acrocentric p-arms also contain Nucleolus organizer regions (NORs), from which ribosomal RNA is transcribed.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] However, a proportion of acrocentric p-arms in cell lines and tissues from normal human donors do not contain detectable NORs.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The domestic horse genome includes one metacentric chromosome that is homologous to two acrocentric chromosomes in the conspecific but undomesticated Przewalski's horse.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] This may reflect either fixation of a balanced Robertsonian translocation in domestic horses or, conversely, fixation of the fission of one metacentric chromosome into two acrocentric chromosomes in Przewalski's horses.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] A similar situation exists between the human and great ape genomes, with a reduction of two acrocentric chromosomes in the great apes to one metacentric chromosome in humans (see aneuploidy and the human chromosome 2).
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Many diseases from the result of unbalanced translocations more frequently involve acrocentric chromosomes than other non-acrocentric chromosomes.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Acrocentric chromosomes are usually located in and around the nucleolus.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] As a result, these chromosomes tend to be less densely packed than chromosomes in the nuclear periphery.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Consistently, chromosomal regions that are less densely packed are also more prone to chromosomal translocations in cancers.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Telocentric chromosomes have a centromere at one end of the chromosome and therefore exhibit only one arm at the cytological (microscopic) level.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] They are not present in humans but can form through cellular chromosomal errors.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Telocentric chromosomes occur naturally in many species, such as the house mouse, in which all chromosomes except the Y are telocentric.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Subtelocentric chromosomes' centromeres are located between the middle and the end of the chromosomes, but reside closer to the end of the chromosomes.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] An acentric chromosome is fragment of a chromosome that lacks a centromere.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Since centromeres are the attachment point for spindle fibers in cell division, acentric fragments are not evenly distributed to daughter cells during cell division.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] As a result, a daughter cell will lack the acentric fragment and deleterious consequences could occur.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Chromosome-breaking events can also generate acentric chromosomes or acentric fragments.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] A dicentric chromosome is an abnormal chromosome with two centromeres, which can be unstable through cell divisions.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] It can form through translocation between or fusion of two chromosome segments, each with a centromere.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Some rearrangements produce both dicentric chromosomes and acentric fragments which can not attach to spindles at mitosis.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The formation of dicentric chromosomes has been attributed to genetic processes, such as Robertsonian translocation and paracentric inversion.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Dicentric chromosomes can have a variety of fates, including mitotic stability.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In some cases, their stability comes from inactivation of one of the two centromeres to make a functionally monocentric chromosome capable of normal transmission to daughter cells during cell division.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] For example, human chromosome 2, which is believed to be the result of a Robertsonian translocation at some point in the evolution between the great apes and *Homo*, has a second, vestigial, centromere near the middle of its long arm.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The monocentric chromosome is a chromosome that has only one centromere in a chromosome and forms a narrow constriction.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Monocentric centromeres are the most common structure on highly repetitive DNA in plants and animals.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Unlike monocentric chromosomes, holocentric chromosomes have no distinct primary constriction when viewed at mitosis.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Instead, spindle fibers attach along almost the entire (Greek: holo-) length of the chromosome.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In holocentric chromosomes centromeric proteins, such as CENPA (CenH3) are spread over the whole chromosome.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The nematode, Caenorhabditis elegans, is a well-known example of an organism with holocentric chromosomes, but this type of centromere can be found in various species, plants, and animals, across eukaryotes.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Holocentromeres are actually composed of multiple distributed centromere units that form a line-like structure along the chromosomes during mitosis.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Alternative or nonconventional strategies are deployed at meiosis to achieve the homologous chromosome pairing and segregation needed to produce viable gametes or gametophytes for sexual reproduction.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Different types of holocentromeres exist in different species, namely with or without centromeric repetitive DNA sequences and with or without CenH3.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Holocentricity has evolved at least 13 times independently in various green algae, protozoans, invertebrates, and different plant families.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Contrary to monocentric species where acentric fragments usually become lost during cell division, the breakage of holocentric chromosomes creates fragments with normal spindle fiber attachment sites.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Because of this, organisms with holocentric chromosomes can more rapidly evolve karyotype variation, able to heal fragmented chromosomes through subsequent addition of telomere caps at the sites of breakage.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Polycentric chromosomes have several kinetochore clusters, i.e. centromes.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The term overlaps partially with "holocentric", but "polycentric" is clearly preferred when discussing defectively formed monocentric chromosomes.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] There is some actual ambiguity as well, as there is no clear line dividing up the transition from kinetochores covering the whole chromosome to distinct clusters.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In other words, the difference between "the whole chromosome is a centrome" and "the chromosome has no centrome" is hazy and usage varies.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Beyond "polycentricity" being used more about defects, there is no clear preference in other topics such as evolutionary origin or kinetochore distribution and detailed structure (e.g. as seen in tagging or genome assembly analysis).
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Even clearly distinct clusters of kinetochore proteins do not necessarily produce more than one constriction: "Metapolycentric" chromosomes feature one elongated constriction of the chromosome, joining a longer segment which is still visibly shorter than the chromatids.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Metapolycentric chromosomes may be a step in the emergence and suppression of centromere drive, a type of meiotic drive that disrupts parity by monocentric centromeres growing additional kinetochore proteins to gain an advantage during meiosis.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In regional centromeres, DNA sequences contribute to but do not define function.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Regional centromeres contain large amounts of DNA and are often packaged into heterochromatin.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In most eukaryotes, the centromere's DNA sequence consists of large arrays of repetitive DNA (e.g. satellite DNA) where the sequence within individual repeat elements is similar but not identical.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In humans, the primary centromeric repeat unit is called α-satellite (or alphoid), although a number of other sequence types are found in this region.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Centromere satellites are hypothesized to evolve by a process called layered expansion.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] They evolve rapidly between species, and analyses in wild mice show that satellite copy number and heterogeneity relates to population origins and subspecies.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Additionally, satellite sequences may be affected by inbreeding.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Point centromeres are smaller and more compact.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] DNA sequences are both necessary and sufficient to specify centromere identity and function in organisms with point centromeres.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In budding yeasts, the centromere region is relatively small (about 125 bp DNA) and contains two highly conserved DNA sequences that serve as binding sites for essential kinetochore proteins.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Since centromeric DNA sequence is not the key determinant of centromeric identity in metazoans, it is thought that epigenetic inheritance plays a major role in specifying the centromere.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The daughter chromosomes will assemble centromeres in the same place as the parent chromosome, independent of sequence.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] It has been proposed that histone H3 variant CENP-A (Centromere Protein A) is the epigenetic mark of the centromere.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The question arises whether there must be still some original way in which the centromere is specified, even if it is subsequently propagated epigenetically.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] If the centromere is inherited epigenetically from one generation to the next, the problem is pushed back to the origin of the first metazoans.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] On the other hand, thanks to comparisons of the centromeres in the X chromosomes, epigenetic and structural variations have been seen in these regions.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In addition, a recent assembly of the human genome has detected a possible mechanism of how pericentromeric and centromeric structures evolve, through a layered expansion model for αSat sequences.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] This model proposes that different αSat sequence repeats emerge periodically and expand within an active vector, displacing old sequences, and becoming the site of kinetochore assembly.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The αSat can originate from the same, or from different vectors.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] As this process is repeated over time, the layers that flank the active centromere shrink and deteriorate.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] This process raises questions about the relationship between this dynamic evolutionary process and the position of the centromere.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The centromeric DNA is normally in a heterochromatin state, which is essential for the recruitment of the cohesin complex that mediates sister chromatid cohesion after DNA replication as well as coordinating sister chromatid separation during anaphase.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In this chromatin, the normal histone H3 is replaced with a centromere-specific variant, CENP-A in humans.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The presence of CENP-A is believed to be important for the assembly of the kinetochore on the centromere.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] CENP-C has been shown to localise almost exclusively to these regions of CENP-A associated chromatin.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In human cells, the histones are found to be most enriched for H4K20me3 and H3K9me3 which are known heterochromatic modifications.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In *Drosophila*, Islands of retroelements are major components of the centromeres.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In the yeast *Schizosaccharomyces pombe* (and probably in other eukaryotes), the formation of centromeric heterochromatin is connected to RNAi.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In rare cases, neocentromeres can form at new sites on a chromosome as a result of a repositioning of the centromere.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] This phenomenon is most well known from human clinical studies and there are currently over 90 known human neocentromeres identified on 20 different chromosomes.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The formation of a neocentromere must be coupled with the inactivation of the previous centromere, since chromosomes with two functional centromeres (Dicentric chromosome) will result in chromosome breakage during mitosis.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] In some unusual cases human neocentromeres have been observed to form spontaneously on fragmented chromosomes.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Some of these new positions were originally euchromatic and lack alpha satellite DNA altogether.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Neocentromeres lack the repetitive structure seen in normal centromeres which suggest that centromere formation is mainly controlled epigenetically.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Over time a neocentromere can accumulate repetitive elements and mature into what is known as an evolutionary new centromere.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] There are several well known examples in primate chromosomes where the centromere position is different from the human centromere of the same chromosome and is thought to be evolutionary new centromeres.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Centromere repositioning and the formation of evolutionary new centromeres has been suggested to be a mechanism of speciation.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Centromere proteins are also the autoantigenic target for some anti-nuclear antibodies, such as anti-centromere antibodies.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] It has been known that centromere misregulation contributes to mis-segregation of chromosomes, which is strongly related to cancer and miscarriage.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Notably, overexpression of many centromere genes have been linked to cancer malignant phenotypes.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Overexpression of these centromere genes can increase genomic instability in cancers.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Elevated genomic instability on one hand relates to malignant phenotypes; on the other hand, it makes the tumor cells more vulnerable to specific adjuvant therapies such as certain chemotherapies and radiotherapy.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] Instability of centromere repetitive DNA was recently shown in cancer and aging.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] When DNA breaks occur at centromeres in the G1 phase of the cell cycle, the cells are able to recruit the homologous recombinational repair machinery to the damaged site, even in the absence of a sister chromatid.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] It appears that homologous recombinational repair can occur at centromeric breaks throughout the cell cycle in order to prevent the activation of inaccurate mutagenic DNA repair pathways and to preserve centromeric integrity.
[src:genetics/acrocentric] The word *centromere* (/ˈsɛntrəˌmɪər/) uses combining forms of *centro- and -mere*, yielding "central part", describing the centromere's location at the center of the chromosome.
[src:genetics/adaptation] In biology, **adaptation** has three related meanings.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Firstly, it is the dynamic evolutionary process of natural selection that fits organisms to their environment, enhancing their evolutionary fitness.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Secondly, it is a state reached by the population during that process.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Thirdly, it is a phenotypic trait or **adaptive trait**, with a functional role in each individual organism, that is maintained and has evolved through natural selection.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Historically, adaptation has been described from the time of the ancient Greek philosophers such as Empedocles and Aristotle.
[src:genetics/adaptation] In 18th and 19th-century natural theology, adaptation was taken as evidence for the existence of a deity.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Charles Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace proposed instead that it was explained by natural selection.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Adaptation is related to biological fitness, which governs the rate of evolution as measured by changes in allele frequencies.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Often, two or more species co-adapt and co-evolve as they develop adaptations that interlock with those of the other species, such as with flowering plants and pollinating insects.
[src:genetics/adaptation] In mimicry, species evolve to resemble other species; in mimicry this is a mutually beneficial co-evolution as each of a group of strongly defended species (such as wasps able to sting) come to advertise their defences in the same way.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Features evolved for one purpose may be co-opted for a different one, as when the insulating feathers of dinosaurs were co-opted for bird flight.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Adaptation is a major topic in the philosophy of biology, as it concerns function and purpose (teleology).
[src:genetics/adaptation] Some biologists try to avoid terms which imply purpose in adaptation, not least because they suggest a deity's intentions, but others note that adaptation is necessarily purposeful.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Adaptation is an observable fact of life accepted by philosophers and natural historians from ancient times, independently of their views on evolution, but their explanations differed.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Empedocles did not believe that adaptation required a final cause (a purpose), but thought that it "came about naturally, since such things survived." Aristotle did believe in final causes, but assumed that species were fixed.
[src:genetics/adaptation] In natural theology, adaptation was interpreted as the work of a deity and as evidence for the existence of God.
[src:genetics/adaptation] William Paley believed that organisms were perfectly adapted to the lives they led, an argument that shadowed Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz, who had argued that God had brought about "the best of all possible worlds." Voltaire's satire Dr.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Pangloss is a parody of this optimistic idea, and David Hume also argued against design.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Charles Darwin broke with the tradition by emphasising the flaws and limitations which occurred in the animal and plant worlds.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Jean-Baptiste Lamarck proposed a tendency for organisms to become more complex, moving up a ladder of progress, plus "the influence of circumstances", usually expressed as *use and disuse*.
[src:genetics/adaptation] This second, subsidiary element of his theory is what is now called Lamarckism, a proto-evolutionary hypothesis of the inheritance of acquired characteristics, intended to explain adaptations by natural means.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Other natural historians, such as Buffon, accepted adaptation, and some also accepted evolution, without voicing their opinions as to the mechanism.
[src:genetics/adaptation] This illustrates the real merit of Darwin and Alfred Russel Wallace, and secondary figures such as Henry Walter Bates, for putting forward a mechanism whose significance had only been glimpsed previously.
[src:genetics/adaptation] A century later, experimental field studies and breeding experiments by people such as E.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Ford and Theodosius Dobzhansky produced evidence that natural selection was not only the 'engine' behind adaptation, but was a much stronger force than had previously been thought.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Adaptation is primarily a process rather than a physical form or part of a body.
[src:genetics/adaptation] An internal parasite (such as a liver fluke) can illustrate the distinction: such a parasite may have a very simple bodily structure, but nevertheless the organism is highly adapted to its specific environment.
[src:genetics/adaptation] From this we see that adaptation is not just a matter of visible traits: in such parasites critical adaptations take place in the life cycle, which is often quite complex.
[src:genetics/adaptation] However, as a practical term, "adaptation" often refers to a *product*: those features of a species which result from the process.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Many aspects of an animal or plant can be correctly called adaptations, though there are always some features whose function remains in doubt.
[src:genetics/adaptation] By using the term *adaptation* for the evolutionary *process*, and *adaptive trait* for the bodily part or function (the product), one may distinguish the two different senses of the word.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Adaptation is one of the two main processes that explain the observed diversity of species, such as the different species of Darwin's finches.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The other process is speciation, in which new species arise, typically through reproductive isolation.
[src:genetics/adaptation] An example widely used today to study the interplay of adaptation and speciation is the evolution of cichlid fish in African lakes, where the question of reproductive isolation is complex.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Adaptation is not always a simple matter where the ideal phenotype evolves for a given environment.
[src:genetics/adaptation] An organism must be viable at all stages of its development and at all stages of its evolution.
[src:genetics/adaptation] This places *constraints* on the evolution of development, behaviour, and structure of organisms.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The main constraint, over which there has been much debate, is the requirement that each genetic and phenotypic change during evolution should be relatively small, because developmental systems are so complex and interlinked.
[src:genetics/adaptation] However, it is not clear what "relatively small" should mean, for example polyploidy in plants is a reasonably common large genetic change.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The origin of eukaryotic endosymbiosis is a more dramatic example.
[src:genetics/adaptation] All adaptations help organisms survive in their ecological niches.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The adaptive traits may be structural, behavioural or physiological.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Structural adaptations are physical features of an organism, such as shape, body covering, armament, and internal organization.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Behavioural adaptations are inherited systems of behaviour, whether inherited in detail as instincts, or as a neuropsychological capacity for learning.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Examples include searching for food, mating, and vocalizations.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Physiological adaptations permit the organism to perform special functions such as making venom, secreting slime, and phototropism, but also involve more general functions such as growth and development, temperature regulation, ionic balance and other aspects of homeostasis.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Adaptation affects all aspects of the life of an organism.
[src:genetics/adaptation] is the state of being adapted: the degree to which an organism is able to live and reproduce in a given set of habitats.
[src:genetics/adaptation] is an aspect of the developmental pattern of the organism which enables or enhances the probability of that organism surviving and reproducing.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Adaptation differs from flexibility, acclimatization, and learning, all of which are changes during life which are not inherited.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Flexibility deals with the relative capacity of an organism to maintain itself in different habitats: its degree of specialization.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Acclimatization describes automatic physiological adjustments during life; learning means alteration in behavioural performance during life.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Flexibility stems from phenotypic plasticity, the ability of an organism with a given genotype (genetic type) to change its phenotype (observable characteristics) in response to changes in its habitat, or to move to a different habitat.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The degree of flexibility is inherited, and varies between individuals.
[src:genetics/adaptation] A highly specialized animal or plant lives only in a well-defined habitat, eats a specific type of food, and cannot survive if its needs are not met.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Many herbivores are like this; extreme examples are koalas which depend on *Eucalyptus*, and giant pandas which require bamboo.
[src:genetics/adaptation] A generalist, on the other hand, eats a range of food, and can survive in many different conditions.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Examples are humans, rats, crabs and many carnivores.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The *tendency* to behave in a specialized or exploratory manner is inherited—it is an adaptation.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Rather different is developmental flexibility: "An animal or plant is developmentally flexible if when it is raised in or transferred to new conditions, it changes in structure so that it is better fitted to survive in the new environment," writes the evolutionary biologist John Maynard Smith.
[src:genetics/adaptation] If humans move to a higher altitude, respiration and physical exertion become a problem, but after spending time in high altitude conditions they acclimatize to the reduced partial pressure of oxygen, such as by producing more red blood cells.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The ability to acclimatize is an adaptation, but the acclimatization itself is not.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The reproductive rate declines, but deaths from some tropical diseases also go down.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Over a longer period of time, some people are better able to reproduce at high altitudes than others.
[src:genetics/adaptation] They contribute more heavily to later generations, and gradually by natural selection the whole population becomes adapted to the new conditions.
[src:genetics/adaptation] This has demonstrably occurred, as the observed performance of long-term communities at higher altitude is significantly better than the performance of new arrivals, even when the new arrivals have had time to acclimatize.
[src:genetics/adaptation] There is a relationship between adaptedness and the concept of fitness used in population genetics.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Differences in fitness between genotypes predict the rate of evolution by natural selection.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Natural selection changes the relative frequencies of alternative phenotypes, insofar as they are heritable.
[src:genetics/adaptation] However, a phenotype with high adaptedness may not have high fitness.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Dobzhansky mentioned the example of the Californian redwood, which is highly adapted, but a relict species in danger of extinction.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Elliott Sober commented that adaptation was a retrospective concept since it implied something about the history of a trait, whereas fitness predicts a trait's future.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The absolute contribution to the next generation by a genotype or a class of genotypes.
[src:genetics/adaptation] when applied to the population as a whole.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The extent to which a phenotype fits its local ecological niche.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Sewall Wright proposed that populations occupy *adaptive peaks* on a fitness landscape.
[src:genetics/adaptation] To evolve to another, higher peak, a population would first have to pass through a valley of maladaptive intermediate stages, and might be "trapped" on a peak that is not optimally adapted.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Before Darwin, adaptation was seen as a fixed relationship between an organism and its habitat.
[src:genetics/adaptation] It was not appreciated that as the climate changed, so did the habitat; and as the habitat changed, so did the biota.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Also, habitats are subject to changes in their biota: for example, invasions of species from other areas.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The relative numbers of species in a given habitat are always changing.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Change is the rule, though much depends on the speed and degree of the change.
[src:genetics/adaptation] When the habitat changes, three main things may happen to a resident population: habitat tracking, genetic change or extinction.
[src:genetics/adaptation] In fact, all three things may occur in sequence.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Of these three effects only genetic change brings about adaptation.
[src:genetics/adaptation] When a habitat changes, the resident population typically moves to more suitable places; this is the typical response of flying insects or oceanic organisms, which have wide (though not unlimited) opportunity for movement.
[src:genetics/adaptation] This common response is called *habitat tracking*.
[src:genetics/adaptation] It is one explanation put forward for the periods of apparent stasis in the fossil record (the punctuated equilibrium theory).
[src:genetics/adaptation] Without mutation, the ultimate source of all genetic variation, there would be no genetic changes and no subsequent adaptation through evolution by natural selection.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Genetic change occurs in a population when mutation increases or decreases in its initial frequency followed by random genetic drift, migration, recombination or natural selection act on this genetic variation.
[src:genetics/adaptation] One example is that the first pathways of enzyme-based metabolism at the very origin of life on Earth may have been co-opted components of the already-existing purine nucleotide metabolism, a metabolic pathway that evolved in an ancient RNA world.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The co-option requires new mutations and through natural selection, the population then adapts genetically to its present circumstances.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Genetic changes may result in entirely new or gradual change to visible structures, or they may adjust physiological activity in a way that suits the habitat.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The varying shapes of the beaks of Darwin's finches, for example, are driven by adaptive mutations in the ALX1 gene.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The coat color of different wild mouse species matches their environments, whether black lava or light sand, owing to adaptive mutations in the melanocortin 1 receptor and other melanin pathway genes.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Physiological resistance to the heart poisons (cardiac glycosides) that monarch butterflies store in their bodies to protect themselves from predators are driven by adaptive mutations in the target of the poison, the sodium pump, resulting in target site insensitivity.
[src:genetics/adaptation] These same adaptive mutations and similar changes at the same amino acid sites were found to evolve in a parallel manner in distantly related insects that feed on the same plants, and even in a bird that feeds on monarchs through convergent evolution, a hallmark of adaptation.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Convergence at the gene-level across distantly related species can arise because of evolutionary constraint.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Habitats and biota do frequently change over time and space.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Therefore, it follows that the process of adaptation is never fully complete.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Over time, it may happen that the environment changes little, and the species comes to fit its surroundings better and better, resulting in stabilizing selection.
[src:genetics/adaptation] On the other hand, it may happen that changes in the environment occur suddenly, and then the species becomes less and less well adapted.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The only way for it to climb back up that fitness peak is via the introduction of new genetic variation for natural selection to act upon.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Seen like this, adaptation is a genetic *tracking process*, which goes on all the time to some extent, but especially when the population cannot or does not move to another, less hostile area.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Given enough genetic change, as well as specific demographic conditions, an adaptation may be enough to bring a population back from the brink of extinction in a process called evolutionary rescue.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Adaptation does affect, to some extent, every species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Leigh Van Valen thought that even in a stable environment, because of antagonistic species interactions and limited resources, a species must constantly had to adapt to maintain its relative standing.
[src:genetics/adaptation] This became known as the Red Queen hypothesis, as seen in host-parasite interactions.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Existing genetic variation and mutation were the traditional sources of material on which natural selection could act.
[src:genetics/adaptation] In addition, horizontal gene transfer is possible between organisms in different species, using mechanisms as varied as gene cassettes, plasmids, transposons and viruses such as bacteriophages.
[src:genetics/adaptation] In coevolution, where the existence of one species is tightly bound up with the life of another species, new or 'improved' adaptations which occur in one species are often followed by the appearance and spread of corresponding features in the other species.
[src:genetics/adaptation] In other words, each species triggers reciprocal natural selection in the other.
[src:genetics/adaptation] These co-adaptational relationships are intrinsically dynamic, and may continue on a trajectory for millions of years, as has occurred in the relationship between flowering plants and pollinating insects.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Bates' work on Amazonian butterflies led him to develop the first scientific account of mimicry, especially the kind of mimicry which bears his name: Batesian mimicry.
[src:genetics/adaptation] This is the mimicry by a palatable species of an unpalatable or noxious species (the model), gaining a selective advantage as predators avoid the model and therefore also the mimic.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Mimicry is thus an anti-predator adaptation.
[src:genetics/adaptation] A common example seen in temperate gardens is the hoverfly (Syrphidae), many of which—though bearing no sting—mimic the warning coloration of aculeate Hymenoptera (wasps and bees).
[src:genetics/adaptation] Such mimicry does not need to be perfect to improve the survival of the palatable species.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Bates, Wallace and Fritz Müller believed that Batesian and Müllerian mimicry provided evidence for the action of natural selection, a view which is now standard amongst biologists.
[src:genetics/adaptation] All adaptations have a downside: horse legs are great for running on grass, but they cannot scratch their backs; mammals' hair helps temperature, but offers a niche for ectoparasites; the only flying penguins do is under water.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Adaptations serving different functions may be mutually destructive.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Compromise and makeshift occur widely, not perfection.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Selection pressures pull in different directions, and the adaptation that results is some kind of compromise.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Consider the antlers of the Irish elk, (often supposed to be far too large; in deer antler size has an allometric relationship to body size).
[src:genetics/adaptation] Antlers serve positively for defence against predators, and to score victories in the annual rut.
[src:genetics/adaptation] But they are costly in terms of resources.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Their size during the last glacial period presumably depended on the relative gain and loss of reproductive capacity in the population of elks during that time.
[src:genetics/adaptation] As another example, camouflage to avoid detection is destroyed when vivid coloration is displayed at mating time.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Here the risk to life is counterbalanced by the necessity for reproduction.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Stream-dwelling salamanders, such as Caucasian salamander or Gold-striped salamander have very slender, long bodies, perfectly adapted to life at the banks of fast small rivers and mountain brooks.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Elongated body protects their larvae from being washed out by current.
[src:genetics/adaptation] However, elongated body increases risk of desiccation and decreases dispersal ability of the salamanders; it also negatively affects their fecundity.
[src:genetics/adaptation] As a result, fire salamander, less perfectly adapted to the mountain brook habitats, is in general more successful, have a higher fecundity and broader geographic range.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The peacock's ornamental train (grown anew in time for each mating season) is a famous adaptation.
[src:genetics/adaptation] It must reduce his maneuverability and flight, and is hugely conspicuous; also, its growth costs food resources.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The recognition of sexual selection was for a long time in abeyance, but has been rehabilitated.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The conflict between the size of the human foetal brain at birth, (which cannot be larger than about 400 cm3, else it will not get through the mother's pelvis) and the size needed for an adult brain (about 1400 cm3), means the brain of a newborn child is quite immature.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The most vital things in human life (locomotion, speech) just have to wait while the brain grows and matures.
[src:genetics/adaptation] That is the result of the birth compromise.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Much of the problem comes from our upright bipedal stance, without which our pelvis could be shaped more suitably for birth.
[src:genetics/adaptation] As another example, the long neck of a giraffe brings benefits but at a cost.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The neck of a giraffe can be up to 2 m (6 ft 7 in) in length.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The benefits are that it can be used for inter-species competition or for foraging on tall trees where shorter herbivores cannot reach.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The cost is that a long neck is heavy and adds to the animal's body mass, requiring additional energy to build the neck and to carry its weight around.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Pre-adaptation occurs when a population has characteristics which by chance are suited for a set of conditions not previously experienced.
[src:genetics/adaptation] For example, the polyploid cordgrass *Spartina townsendii* is better adapted than either of its parent species to their own habitat of saline marsh and mud-flats.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Among domestic animals, the White Leghorn chicken is markedly more resistant to vitamin B1 deficiency than other breeds; on a plentiful diet this makes no difference, but on a restricted diet this preadaptation could be decisive.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Pre-adaptation may arise because a natural population carries a huge quantity of genetic variability.
[src:genetics/adaptation] In diploid eukaryotes, this is a consequence of the system of sexual reproduction, where mutant alleles get partially shielded, for example, by genetic dominance.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Microorganisms, with their huge populations, also carry a great deal of genetic variability.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The word is controversial because it is teleological and the entire concept of natural selection depends on the presence of genetic variation, regardless of the population size of a species in question.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Features that now appear as adaptations sometimes arose by co-option of existing traits, evolved for some other purpose.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The classic example is the ear ossicles of mammals, which we know from paleontological and embryological evidence originated in the upper and lower jaws and the hyoid bone of their synapsid ancestors, and further back still were part of the gill arches of early fish.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The word *exaptation* was coined to cover these common evolutionary shifts in function.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The flight feathers of birds evolved from the much earlier feathers of dinosaurs, which might have been used for insulation or for display.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Animals including earthworms, beavers and humans use some of their adaptations to modify their surroundings, so as to maximize their chances of surviving and reproducing.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Beavers create dams and lodges, changing the ecosystems of the valleys around them.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Earthworms, as Darwin noted, improve the topsoil in which they live by incorporating organic matter.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Humans have constructed extensive civilizations with cities in environments as varied as the Arctic and hot deserts.
[src:genetics/adaptation] In all three cases, the construction and maintenance of ecological niches helps drive the continued selection of the genes of these animals, in an environment that the animals have modified.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Some traits do not appear to be adaptive as they have a neutral or deleterious effect on fitness in the current environment.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Another possibility is that a trait may have been adaptive at some point in an organism's evolutionary history, but a change in habitats caused what used to be an adaptation to become unnecessary or even maladapted.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Many organisms have vestigial organs, which are the remnants of fully functional structures in their ancestors.
[src:genetics/adaptation] As a result of changes in lifestyle the organs became redundant, and are either not functional or reduced in functionality.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Since any structure represents some kind of cost to the general economy of the body, an advantage may accrue from their elimination once they are not functional.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Examples: wisdom teeth in humans; the loss of pigment and functional eyes in cave fauna; the loss of structure in endoparasites.
[src:genetics/adaptation] If a population cannot move or change sufficiently to preserve its long-term viability, then it will become extinct, at least in that locale.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The species may or may not survive in other locales.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Species extinction occurs when the death rate over the entire species exceeds the birth rate for a long enough period for the species to disappear.
[src:genetics/adaptation] It was an observation of Van Valen that groups of species tend to have a characteristic and fairly regular rate of extinction.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The first stage in the evolution of life on earth is often hypothesized to be the RNA world in which short self-replicating RNA molecules proliferated before the evolution of DNA and proteins.
[src:genetics/adaptation] By this hypothesis, life started when RNA chains began to self-replicate, initiating the three mechanisms of Darwinian selection: heritability, variation of type, and competition for resources.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The fitness of an RNA replicator (its per capita rate of increase) would likely have been a function of its intrinsic adaptive capacities, determined by its nucleotide sequence, and the availability of resources.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The three primary adaptive capacities may have been: (1) replication with moderate fidelity, giving rise to heritability while allowing variation of type, (2) resistance to decay, and (3) acquisition of resources.
[src:genetics/adaptation] These adaptive capacities would have been determined by the folded configurations of the RNA replicators resulting from their nucleotide sequences.
[src:genetics/adaptation] In his biology, Aristotle introduced teleology to describe the adaptedness of organisms, but without accepting the supernatural intention built into Plato's thinking, which Aristotle rejected.
[src:genetics/adaptation] Modern biologists continue to face the same difficulty.
[src:genetics/adaptation] On the one hand, adaptation is purposeful: natural selection chooses what works and eliminates what does not.
[src:genetics/adaptation] On the other hand, biologists by and large reject conscious purpose in evolution.
[src:genetics/adaptation] The dilemma gave rise to a famous joke by the evolutionary biologist Haldane: "Teleology is like a mistress to a biologist: he cannot live without her but he's unwilling to be seen with her in public.'" David Hull commented that Haldane's mistress "has become a lawfully wedded wife.
[src:genetics/adenine] Adenine has a central role in cellular respiration.
[src:genetics/adenine] It is part of adenosine triphosphate which provides the energy that drives and supports most activities in living cells, such as protein synthesis, muscle contraction, and nerve impulse propagation.
[src:genetics/adenine] In respiration it also participates as part of the cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide, flavin adenine dinucleotide, and coenzyme A.
[src:genetics/adenine] It is also part of adenosine, adenosine monophosphate, cyclic adenosine monophosphate, adenosine diphosphate, and S-adenosylmethionine.
[src:genetics/adenine] Adenine forms several tautomers, compounds that can be rapidly interconverted and are often considered equivalent.
[src:genetics/adenine] However, in isolated conditions, i.e. in an inert gas matrix and in the gas phase, mainly the 9H-adenine tautomer is found.
[src:genetics/adenine] Purine metabolism involves the formation of adenine and guanine.
[src:genetics/adenine] Both adenine and guanine are derived from the nucleotide inosine monophosphate (IMP), which in turn is synthesized from a pre-existing ribose phosphate through a complex pathway using atoms from the amino acids glycine, glutamine, and aspartic acid, as well as the coenzyme tetrahydrofolate.
[src:genetics/adenine] Patented August 20, 1968, the current recognized method of industrial-scale production of adenine involves heating formamide under 120 °C.
[src:genetics/adenine] Adenine is one of the two purine nucleobases (the other being guanine) used in forming nucleotides of the nucleic acids.
[src:genetics/adenine] In DNA, adenine binds to thymine via two hydrogen bonds to assist in stabilizing the nucleic acid structures.
[src:genetics/adenine] In RNA, which is used for protein synthesis, adenine binds to uracil.
[src:genetics/adenine] Adenine forms adenosine, a nucleoside, when attached to ribose, and deoxyadenosine when attached to deoxyribose.
[src:genetics/adenine] It forms adenosine triphosphate (ATP), a nucleoside triphosphate, when three phosphate groups are added to adenosine.
[src:genetics/adenine] Adenosine triphosphate is used in cellular metabolism as one of the basic methods of transferring chemical energy between chemical reactions.
[src:genetics/adenine] ATP is thus a derivative of adenine, adenosine, cyclic adenosine monophosphate, and adenosine diphosphate.
[src:genetics/adenine] In older literature, adenine was sometimes called **Vitamin B4**, but is no longer considered a vitamin.
[src:genetics/adenine] Due to it being synthesized by the body and not essential to be obtained by diet, it does not meet the definition of vitamin and is no longer part of the Vitamin B complex.
[src:genetics/adenine] However, two B vitamins, niacin and riboflavin, bind with adenine to form the essential cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD) and flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD), respectively.
[src:genetics/adenine] Hermann Emil Fischer was one of the early scientists to study adenine.
[src:genetics/adenine] It was named in 1885 by Albrecht Kossel after Greek *ἀδήν* aden "gland", in reference to the pancreas, from which Kossel's sample had been extracted.
[src:genetics/adenine] Adenine can be prepared from ammonia and hydrogen cyanide (HCN) in aqueous solution, a process that has implications for the origin of life on Earth.
[src:genetics/adenine] On August 8, 2011, a report, based on NASA studies with meteorites found on Earth, was published suggesting building blocks of DNA and RNA (adenine, guanine and related organic molecules) may have been formed extraterrestrially in outer space.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] When consumed in a metabolic process, ATP converts either to adenosine diphosphate (ADP) or to adenosine monophosphate (AMP).
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Other processes, such as oxidative phosphorylation or substrate-level phosphorylation, regenerate ATP.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a precursor to DNA and RNA, and is used as a coenzyme.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Daily, an average adult human recycles through synthesis and hydrolysis around 50 kilograms of ATP (about 100 moles).
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] From the perspective of biochemistry, ATP is classified as a nucleoside triphosphate, which indicates that it consists of three components: a nitrogenous base (adenine), the sugar ribose, and the triphosphate.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP consists of three parts: a sugar, an amine base, and a phosphate group.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] More specifically, ATP consists of an adenine attached by the #9-nitrogen atom to the 1′ carbon atom of a sugar (ribose), which in turn is attached at the 5' carbon atom of the sugar to a triphosphate group.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In its many reactions related to metabolism, the adenine and sugar groups remain unchanged, but the triphosphate is converted to di- and monophosphate, giving respectively the derivatives ADP and AMP.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The three phosphoryl groups are labeled as alpha (α), beta (β), and, for the terminal phosphate, gamma (γ).
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In neutral solution, ionized ATP exists mostly as ATP4−, with a small proportion of ATP3−.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Polyanionic and featuring a potentially chelating polyphosphate group, ATP binds metal cations with high affinity.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding constant for Mg2+ is (9554).
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The binding of a divalent cation, almost always magnesium, strongly affects the interaction of ATP with various proteins.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Due to the strength of the ATP-Mg2+ interaction, ATP exists in the cell mostly as a complex with Mg2+ bonded to the phosphate oxygen centers.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] A second magnesium ion is critical for ATP binding in the kinase domain.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The presence of Mg2+ regulates kinase activity.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] It is interesting from an RNA world perspective that ATP can carry a Mg2+ ion which catalyzes RNA polymerization.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Salts of ATP can be isolated as colorless solids.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is stable in aqueous solutions between pH 6.8 and 7.4 (in the absence of catalysts).
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] At more extreme pH levels, it rapidly hydrolyses to ADP and phosphate.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Living cells maintain the ratio of ATP to ADP at a point ten orders of magnitude from equilibrium, with ATP concentrations fivefold higher than the concentration of ADP.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In the context of biochemical reactions, the P-O-P bonds are frequently referred to as *high-energy bonds*.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] releases Δ*G*°' = −30.5 kJ/mol (−7.3 kcal/mol) of Gibbs free energy under standard conditions when all metabolite concentrations are 1 mol/L.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] This may differ under physiological conditions if the reactant and products are not exactly in these ionization states.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] At cytoplasmic conditions, where the ADP/ATP ratio is 10 orders of magnitude from equilibrium, the Δ*G* is around −57 kJ/mol.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Along with pH, the free energy change of ATP hydrolysis is also associated with Mg2+ concentration, from ΔG°' = −35.7 kJ/mol at a Mg2+ concentration of zero, to ΔG°' = −31 kJ/mol at [Mg2+] = 5 mM.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Higher concentrations of Mg2+ decrease free energy released in the reaction due to binding of Mg2+ ions to negatively charged oxygen atoms of ATP at pH 7.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] A typical intracellular concentration of ATP is 1–10 μmol per gram of muscle tissue in a variety of eukaryotes.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The dephosphorylation of ATP and rephosphorylation of ADP and AMP occur repeatedly in the course of aerobic metabolism.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can be produced by a number of distinct cellular processes; the three main pathways in eukaryotes are (1) glycolysis, (2) the citric acid cycle/oxidative phosphorylation, and (3) beta-oxidation.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The overall process of oxidizing glucose to carbon dioxide, the combination of pathways 1 and 2, known as cellular respiration, produces about 30 equivalents of ATP from each molecule of glucose.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP production by a non-photosynthetic aerobic eukaryote occurs mainly in the mitochondria, which comprise nearly 25% of the volume of a typical cell.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In glycolysis, glucose and glycerol are metabolized to pyruvate.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis generates two equivalents of ATP through substrate phosphorylation catalyzed by two enzymes, phosphoglycerate kinase (PGK) and pyruvate kinase.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Two equivalents of nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NADH) are also produced, which can be oxidized via the electron transport chain and result in the generation of additional ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The pyruvate generated as an end-product of glycolysis is a substrate for the citric acid cycle.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is viewed as consisting of two phases with five steps each.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In phase 1, "the preparatory phase", glucose is converted to 2 d-glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (g3p).
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] One ATP is invested in Step 1, and another ATP is invested in Step 3.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Steps 1 and 3 of glycolysis are referred to as "Priming Steps".
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In Phase 2, two equivalents of g3p are converted to two pyruvates.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Also, in Step 10, two further equivalents of ATP are produced.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In Steps 7 and 10, ATP is generated from ADP.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] A net of two ATPs is formed in the glycolysis cycle.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The glycolysis pathway is later associated with the Citric Acid Cycle, which produces additional equivalents of ATP.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Glycolysis is regulated allosterically by a number of metabolic compounds.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] For example, hexokinase is directly inhibited by its product, glucose-6-phosphate, and pyruvate kinase is inhibited by ATP itself.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The main control point for the glycolytic pathway is phosphofructokinase 1 (PFK1), which is allosterically inhibited by high concentrations of ATP and activated by high concentrations of AMP.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The inhibition of PFK1 by ATP is unusual since ATP is also a substrate in the reaction catalyzed by PFK1.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The active form of PFK1 enzyme is a tetramer that exists in two conformations, only one of which binds the second substrate fructose-6-phosphate (F6P).
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The PFK1 enzyme has two binding sites for ATP – the active site is accessible in either protein conformation, but ATP binding to the inhibitor site stabilizes the conformation that binds F6P poorly.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] A number of other small molecules can compensate for the ATP-induced shift in equilibrium conformation and reactivate PFK1, including cyclic AMP, ammonium ions, inorganic phosphate, fructose 1,6-bisphosphate and fructose 2,6-bisphosphate.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In the mitochondrion, pyruvate is oxidized by the pyruvate dehydrogenase complex to the acetyl group, which is fully oxidized to carbon dioxide by the citric acid cycle.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] NADH and FADH2 are recycled (to NAD+ and FAD, respectively) by oxidative phosphorylation, generating additional ATP.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The oxidation of NADH results in the synthesis of 2–3 equivalents of ATP, and the oxidation of one FADH2 yields between 1–2 equivalents of ATP.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of cellular ATP is generated by this process.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Although the citric acid cycle itself does not involve molecular oxygen, it is an obligately aerobic process because O2 is used to recycle the NADH and FADH2.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In the absence of oxygen, the citric acid cycle ceases.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The generation of ATP by the mitochondrion from cytosolic NADH relies on the malate-aspartate shuttle (and to a lesser extent, the glycerol-phosphate shuttle) because the inner mitochondrial membrane is impermeable to NADH and NAD+.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Instead of transferring the generated NADH, a malate dehydrogenase enzyme converts oxaloacetate to malate, which is translocated to the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Another malate dehydrogenase-catalyzed reaction occurs in the opposite direction, producing oxaloacetate and NADH from the newly transported malate and the mitochondrion's interior store of NAD+.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] A transaminase converts the oxaloacetate to aspartate for transport back across the membrane and into the intermembrane space.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the passage of electrons from NADH and FADH2 through the electron transport chain releases the energy to pump protons out of the mitochondrial matrix and into the intermembrane space.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] This pumping generates a proton motive force that is the net effect of a pH gradient and an electric potential gradient across the inner mitochondrial membrane.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Flow of protons down this potential gradient – that is, from the intermembrane space to the matrix – yields ATP by ATP synthase.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Most of the ATP synthesized in the mitochondria will be used for cellular processes in the cytosol; thus it must be exported from its site of synthesis in the mitochondrial matrix.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP outward movement is favored by the inner mitochondrial membrane's electrochemical potential because the cytosol has a relatively positive charge compared to the relatively negative matrix.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] For every ATP transported out, it costs 1 H+.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Therefore, making and exporting one ATP requires 4H+.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The inner membrane contains an antiporter, the ADP/ATP translocase, which is an integral membrane protein used to exchange newly synthesized ATP in the matrix for ADP in the intermembrane space.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The citric acid cycle is regulated mainly by the availability of key substrates, particularly the ratio of NAD+ to NADH and the concentrations of calcium, inorganic phosphate, ATP, ADP, and AMP.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Citrate – the ion that gives its name to the cycle – is a feedback inhibitor of citrate synthase and also inhibits PFK, providing a direct link between the regulation of the citric acid cycle and glycolysis.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In the presence of air and various cofactors and enzymes, fatty acids are converted to acetyl-CoA.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Each cycle of beta-oxidation shortens the fatty acid chain by two carbon atoms and produces one equivalent each of acetyl-CoA, NADH, and FADH2.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The acetyl-CoA is metabolized by the citric acid cycle to generate ATP, while the NADH and FADH2 are used by oxidative phosphorylation to generate ATP.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Dozens of ATP equivalents are generated by the beta-oxidation of a single long acyl chain.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In oxidative phosphorylation, the key control point is the reaction catalyzed by cytochrome c oxidase, which is regulated by the availability of its substrate – the reduced form of cytochrome c.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, a high ratio of [NADH] to [NAD+] or a high ratio of [ADP] [Pi] to [ATP] imply a high amount of reduced cytochrome c and a high level of cytochrome c oxidase activity.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] An additional level of regulation is introduced by the transport rates of ATP and NADH between the mitochondrial matrix and the cytoplasm.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies can be used as fuels, yielding 22 ATP and 2 GTP molecules per acetoacetate molecule when oxidized in the mitochondria.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies are transported from the liver to other tissues, where acetoacetate and *beta*-hydroxybutyrate can be reconverted to acetyl-CoA to produce reducing equivalents (NADH and FADH2), via the citric acid cycle.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Ketone bodies cannot be used as fuel by the liver, because the liver lacks the enzyme β-ketoacyl-CoA transferase, also called thiolase.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in low concentrations is taken up by the liver and undergoes detoxification through the methylglyoxal pathway which ends with lactate.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetoacetate in high concentrations is absorbed by cells other than those in the liver and enters a different pathway via 1,2-propanediol.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Though the pathway follows a different series of steps requiring ATP, 1,2-propanediol can be turned into pyruvate.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Fermentation is the metabolism of organic compounds in the absence of air.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] It involves substrate-level phosphorylation in the absence of a respiratory electron transport chain.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Anaerobic respiration is respiration in the absence of O2.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Prokaryotes can utilize a variety of electron acceptors.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] These include nitrate, sulfate, and carbon dioxide.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In anaerobic organisms and prokaryotes, different pathways result in ATP.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is produced in the chloroplasts of green plants in a process similar to oxidative phosphorylation, called photophosphorylation.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP can also be synthesized through several so-called "replenishment" reactions catalyzed by the enzyme families of nucleoside diphosphate kinases (NDKs), which use other nucleoside triphosphates as a high-energy phosphate donor, and the ATP:guanido-phosphotransferase family.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In plants, ATP is synthesized in the thylakoid membrane of the chloroplast.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is called photophosphorylation.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The "machinery" is similar to that in mitochondria except that light energy is used to pump protons across a membrane to produce a proton-motive force.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP synthase then ensues exactly as in oxidative phosphorylation.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Some of the ATP produced in the chloroplasts is consumed in the Calvin cycle, which produces triose sugars.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The total quantity of ATP in the human body is about 0.1 mol/L.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The majority of ATP is recycled from ADP by the aforementioned processes.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Thus, at any given time, the total amount of ATP + ADP remains fairly constant.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The energy used by human cells in an adult requires the hydrolysis of 100 to 150 mol/L of ATP daily, which means a human will typically use their body weight worth of ATP over the course of the day.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Each equivalent of ATP is recycled 1000–1500 times during a single day (150 / 0.1 = 1500), at approximately 9×1020 molecules/s.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The conversion of ATP to ADP is the principal mechanism for energy supply in biological processes.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] However, removing a phosphate group from ADP to produce adenosine monophosphate (AMP) also produces extra energy.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is involved in signal transduction by serving as substrate for kinases, enzymes that transfer phosphate groups.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Kinases are the most common ATP-binding proteins.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] They share a small number of common folds.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Phosphorylation of a protein by a kinase can activate a cascade such as the mitogen-activated protein kinase cascade.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is also a substrate of adenylate cyclase, most commonly in G protein-coupled receptor signal transduction pathways and is transformed to second messenger, cyclic AMP, which is involved in triggering calcium signals by the release of calcium from intracellular stores.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] This form of signal transduction is particularly important in brain function, although it is involved in the regulation of a multitude of other cellular processes.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is one of four monomers required in the synthesis of RNA.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The process is promoted by RNA polymerases.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] A similar process occurs in the formation of DNA, except that ATP is first converted to the deoxyribonucleotide dATP.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Like many condensation reactions in nature, DNA replication and DNA transcription also consume ATP.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl-tRNA synthetase enzymes consume ATP in the attachment tRNA to amino acids, forming aminoacyl-tRNA complexes.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Aminoacyl transferase binds AMP-amino acid to tRNA.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The amino acid is coupled to the penultimate nucleotide at the 3′-end of the tRNA (the A in the sequence CCA) via an ester bond (roll over in illustration).
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Transporting chemicals out of a cell against a gradient is often associated with ATP hydrolysis.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Transport is mediated by ATP binding cassette transporters.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The human genome encodes 48 ABC transporters, that are used for exporting drugs, lipids, and other compounds.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells secrete ATP to communicate with other cells in a process called purinergic signalling.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP serves as a neurotransmitter in many parts of the nervous system, modulates ciliary beating, affects vascular oxygen supply etc.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is either secreted directly across the cell membrane through channel proteins or is pumped into vesicles which then fuse with the membrane.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Cells detect ATP using the purinergic receptor proteins P2X and P2Y.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has been shown to be a critically important signalling molecule for microglia - neuron interactions in the adult brain, as well as during brain development.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Furthermore, tissue-injury induced ATP-signalling is a major factor in rapid microglial phenotype changes.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Muscle contractions are regulated by signaling pathways, although different muscle types being regulated by specific pathways and stimuli based on their particular function.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] However, in all muscle types, contraction is performed by the proteins actin and myosin.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] When ATPase hydrolyzes the bound ATP into ADP and inorganic phosphate, myosin is positioned in a way that it can bind to actin.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Myosin bound by ADP and Pi forms cross-bridges with actin and the subsequent release of ADP and Pi releases energy as the power stroke.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The power stroke causes actin filament to slide past the myosin filament, shortening the muscle and causing a contraction.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Another ATP molecule can then bind to myosin, releasing it from actin and allowing this process to repeat.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP has recently been proposed to act as a biological hydrotrope and has been shown to affect proteome-wide solubility.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Acetyl phosphate (AcP), a precursor to ATP, can readily be synthesized at modest yields from thioacetate in pH 7 and 20 °C and pH 8 and 50 °C, although acetyl phosphate is less stable in warmer temperatures and alkaline conditions than in cooler and acidic to neutral conditions.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] It is unable to promote polymerization of ribonucleotides and amino acids and was only capable of phosphorylation of organic compounds.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that it can promote aggregation and stabilization of AMP in the presence of Na+, aggregation of nucleotides could promote polymerization above 75 °C in the absence of Na+.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] It is possible that polymerization promoted by AcP could occur at mineral surfaces.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] It was shown that ADP can only be phosphorylated to ATP by AcP and other nucleoside triphosphates were not phosphorylated by AcP.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] This might explain why all lifeforms use ATP to drive biochemical reactions.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Biochemistry laboratories often use *in vitro* studies to explore ATP-dependent molecular processes.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP analogs are also used in X-ray crystallography to determine a protein structure in complex with ATP, often together with other substrates.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Enzyme inhibitors of ATP-dependent enzymes such as kinases are needed to examine the binding sites and transition states involved in ATP-dependent reactions.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Most useful ATP analogs cannot be hydrolyzed as ATP would be; instead, they trap the enzyme in a structure closely related to the ATP-bound state.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Adenosine 5′-(γ-thiotriphosphate) is an extremely common ATP analog in which one of the gamma-phosphate oxygens is replaced by a sulfur atom; this anion is hydrolyzed at a dramatically slower rate than ATP itself and functions as an inhibitor of ATP-dependent processes.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] In crystallographic studies, hydrolysis transition states are modeled by the bound vanadate ion.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Caution is warranted in interpreting the results of experiments using ATP analogs, since some enzymes can hydrolyze them at appreciable rates at high concentration.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP is used intravenously for some heart-related conditions.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] ATP was discovered in 1929 from muscle tissue by Karl Lohmann and Jendrassik and, independently, by Cyrus Fiske and Yellapragada Subba Rao of Harvard Medical School, both teams competing against each other to find an assay for phosphorus.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] It was proposed to be the intermediary between energy-yielding and energy-requiring reactions in cells by Fritz Albert Lipmann in 1941.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] He played a major role in establishing that ATP is the energy currency of a cell.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] It was first synthesized in the laboratory by Alexander Todd in 1948, and he was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1957 partly for this work.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1978 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was awarded to Peter Dennis Mitchell for the discovery of the chemiosmotic mechanism of ATP synthesis.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] The 1997 Nobel Prize in Chemistry was divided, one half jointly to Paul D.
[src:genetics/adenosine-triphosphate] Walker "for their elucidation of the enzymatic mechanism underlying the synthesis of adenosine triphosphate (ATP)" and the other half to Jens C.
[src:genetics/genetics] Trait inheritance and molecular inheritance mechanisms of genes are still primary principles of genetics in the 21st century, but modern genetics has expanded to study the function and behavior of genes.
[src:genetics/genetics] Gene structure and function, variation, and distribution are studied within the context of the cell, the organism (e.g. dominance), and within the context of a population.
[src:genetics/genetics] Genetics has given rise to a number of subfields, including molecular genetics, epigenetics, population genetics, and paleogenetics.
[src:genetics/genetics] Organisms studied within the broad field span the domains of life (archaea, bacteria, and eukarya).
[src:genetics/genetics] Genetic processes work in combination with an organism's environment and experiences to influence development and behavior, often referred to as nature versus nurture.
[src:genetics/genetics] The intracellular or extracellular environment of a living cell or organism may increase or decrease gene transcription.
[src:genetics/genetics] A classic example is two seeds of genetically identical corn, one placed in a temperate climate and one in an arid climate (lacking sufficient waterfall or rain).
[src:genetics/genetics] While the average height the two corn stalks could grow to is genetically determined, the one in the arid climate only grows to half the height of the one in the temperate climate due to lack of water and nutrients in its environment.
[src:genetics/genetics] William Bateson coined *genetics* from the ancient Greek γενετικός **genetikos** meaning "genitive"/"generative", which in turn derives from γένεσις **genesis** meaning "origin".
[src:genetics/genetics] The observation that living things inherit traits from their parents has been used since prehistoric times to improve crop plants and animals through selective breeding.
[src:genetics/genetics] The modern science of genetics, seeking to understand this process, began with the work of the Augustinian friar Gregor Mendel in the mid-19th century.
[src:genetics/genetics] Prior to Mendel, Imre Festetics, a Hungarian noble, who lived in Kőszeg before Mendel, was the first who used the word "genetic" in hereditarian context, and is considered the first geneticist.
[src:genetics/genetics] He described several rules of biological inheritance in his work *The genetic laws of nature* (Die genetischen Gesetze der Natur, 1819).
[src:genetics/genetics] His second law is the same as that which Mendel published.
[src:genetics/genetics] In his third law, he developed the basic principles of mutation (he can be considered a forerunner of Hugo de Vries).
[src:genetics/genetics] Festetics argued that changes observed in the generation of farm animals, plants, and humans are the result of scientific laws.
[src:genetics/genetics] Festetics empirically deduced that organisms inherit their characteristics, not acquire them.
[src:genetics/genetics] He recognized recessive traits and inherent variation by postulating that traits of past generations could reappear later, and organisms could produce progeny with different attributes.
[src:genetics/genetics] These observations represent an important prelude to Mendel's theory of particulate inheritance insofar as it features a transition of heredity from its status as myth to that of a scientific discipline, by providing a fundamental theoretical basis for genetics in the twentieth century.
[src:genetics/genetics] Other theories of inheritance preceded Mendel's work.
[src:genetics/genetics] A popular theory during the 19th century, and implied by Charles Darwin's 1859 *On the Origin of Species*, was blending inheritance: the idea that individuals inherit a smooth blend of traits from their parents.
[src:genetics/genetics] Mendel's work provided examples where traits were definitely not blended after hybridization, showing that traits are produced by combinations of distinct genes rather than a continuous blend.
[src:genetics/genetics] Blending of traits in the progeny is now explained by the action of multiple genes with quantitative effects.
[src:genetics/genetics] Another theory that had some support at that time was the inheritance of acquired characteristics: the belief that individuals inherit traits strengthened by their parents.
[src:genetics/genetics] This theory (commonly associated with Jean-Baptiste Lamarck) is now known to be wrong—the experiences of individuals do not affect the genes they pass to their children.
[src:genetics/genetics] Other theories included Darwin's pangenesis (which had both acquired and inherited aspects) and Francis Galton's reformulation of pangenesis as both particulate and inherited.
[src:genetics/genetics] Modern genetics started with Mendel's studies of the nature of inheritance in plants.
[src:genetics/genetics] In his paper "*Versuche über Pflanzenhybriden*" ("Experiments on Plant Hybridization"), presented in 1865 to the *Naturforschender Verein* (Society for Research in Nature) in Brno, Mendel traced the inheritance patterns of certain traits in pea plants and described them mathematically.
[src:genetics/genetics] Although this pattern of inheritance could only be observed for a few traits, Mendel's work suggested that heredity was particulate, not acquired, and that the inheritance patterns of many traits could be explained through simple rules and ratios.
[src:genetics/genetics] The importance of Mendel's work did not gain wide understanding until 1900, after his death, when Hugo de Vries and other scientists rediscovered his research.
[src:genetics/genetics] William Bateson, a proponent of Mendel's work, coined the word *genetics* in 1905.
[src:genetics/genetics] The adjective *genetic*, derived from the Greek word *genesis*—γένεσις, "origin", predates the noun and was first used in a biological sense in 1860.
[src:genetics/genetics] Bateson both acted as a mentor and was aided significantly by the work of other scientists from Newnham College at Cambridge, specifically the work of Becky Saunders, Nora Darwin Barlow, and Muriel Wheldale Onslow.
[src:genetics/genetics] Bateson popularized the usage of the word *genetics* to describe the study of inheritance in his inaugural address to the Third International Conference on Plant Hybridization in London in 1906.
[src:genetics/genetics] After the rediscovery of Mendel's work, scientists tried to determine which molecules in the cell were responsible for inheritance.
[src:genetics/genetics] In 1900, Nettie Stevens began studying the mealworm.
[src:genetics/genetics] Over the next 11 years, she discovered that females only had the X chromosome and males had both X and Y chromosomes.
[src:genetics/genetics] She was able to conclude that sex is a chromosomal factor and is determined by the male.
[src:genetics/genetics] In 1911, Thomas Hunt Morgan argued that genes are on chromosomes, based on observations of a sex-linked white eye mutation in fruit flies.
[src:genetics/genetics] In 1913, his student Alfred Sturtevant used the phenomenon of genetic linkage to show that genes are arranged linearly on the chromosome.
[src:genetics/genetics] Although genes were known to exist on chromosomes, chromosomes are composed of both protein and DNA, and scientists did not know which of the two was responsible for inheritance.
[src:genetics/genetics] In 1928, Frederick Griffith discovered the phenomenon of transformation: dead bacteria could transfer genetic material to "transform" other still-living bacteria.
[src:genetics/genetics] Sixteen years later, in 1944, the Avery–MacLeod–McCarty experiment identified DNA as the molecule responsible for transformation.
[src:genetics/genetics] The role of the nucleus as the repository of genetic information in eukaryotes had been established by Hämmerling in 1943 in his work on the single celled alga *Acetabularia*.
[src:genetics/genetics] The Hershey–Chase experiment in 1952 confirmed that DNA (rather than protein) is the genetic material of the viruses that infect bacteria, providing further evidence that DNA is the molecule responsible for inheritance.
[src:genetics/genetics] James Watson and Francis Crick determined the structure of DNA in 1953, using the X-ray crystallography work of Rosalind Franklin and Maurice Wilkins that indicated DNA has a helical structure (i.e., shaped like a corkscrew).
[src:genetics/genetics] Their double-helix model had two strands of DNA with the nucleotides pointing inward, each matching a complementary nucleotide on the other strand to form what look like rungs on a twisted ladder.
[src:genetics/genetics] This structure showed that genetic information exists in the sequence of nucleotides on each strand of DNA.
[src:genetics/genetics] The structure also suggested a simple method for replication: if the strands are separated, new partner strands can be reconstructed for each based on the sequence of the old strand.
[src:genetics/genetics] This property is what gives DNA its semi-conservative nature where one strand of new DNA is from an original parent strand.
[src:genetics/genetics] Although the structure of DNA showed how inheritance works, it was still not known how DNA influences the behavior of cells.
[src:genetics/genetics] In the following years, scientists tried to understand how DNA controls the process of protein production.
[src:genetics/genetics] It was discovered that the cell uses DNA as a template to create matching messenger RNA, molecules with nucleotides very similar to DNA.
[src:genetics/genetics] The nucleotide sequence of a messenger RNA is used to create an amino acid sequence in protein; this translation between nucleotide sequences and amino acid sequences is known as the genetic code.
[src:genetics/genetics] With the newfound molecular understanding of inheritance came an explosion of research.
[src:genetics/genetics] A notable theory arose from Tomoko Ohta in 1973 with her amendment to the neutral theory of molecular evolution through publishing the nearly neutral theory of molecular evolution.
[src:genetics/genetics] In this theory, Ohta stressed the importance of natural selection and the environment to the rate at which genetic evolution occurs.
[src:genetics/genetics] One important development was chain-termination DNA sequencing in 1977 by Frederick Sanger.
[src:genetics/genetics] This technology allows scientists to read the nucleotide sequence of a DNA molecule.
[src:genetics/genetics] In 1983, Kary Banks Mullis developed the polymerase chain reaction, providing a quick way to isolate and amplify a specific section of DNA from a mixture.
[src:genetics/genetics] The efforts of the Human Genome Project, Department of Energy, NIH, and parallel private efforts by Celera Genomics led to the sequencing of the human genome in 2003.
[src:genetics/genetics] At its most fundamental level, inheritance in organisms occurs by passing discrete heritable units, called genes, from parents to offspring.
[src:genetics/genetics] This property was first observed by Gregor Mendel, who studied the segregation of heritable traits in pea plants, showing for example that flowers on a single plant were either purple or white—but never an intermediate between the two colors.
[src:genetics/genetics] The discrete versions of the same gene controlling the inherited appearance (phenotypes) are called alleles.
[src:genetics/genetics] In the case of the pea, which is a diploid species, each individual plant has two copies of each gene, one copy inherited from each parent.
[src:genetics/genetics] Many species, including humans, have this pattern of inheritance.
[src:genetics/genetics] Diploid organisms with two copies of the same allele of a given gene are called homozygous at that gene locus, while organisms with two different alleles of a given gene are called heterozygous.
[src:genetics/genetics] The set of alleles for a given organism is called its genotype, while the observable traits of the organism are called its phenotype.
[src:genetics/genetics] When organisms are heterozygous at a gene, often one allele is called dominant as its qualities dominate the phenotype of the organism, while the other allele is called recessive as its qualities recede and are not observed.
[src:genetics/genetics] Some alleles do not have complete dominance and instead have incomplete dominance by expressing an intermediate phenotype, or codominance by expressing both alleles at once.
[src:genetics/genetics] When a pair of organisms reproduce sexually, their offspring randomly inherit one of the two alleles from each parent.
[src:genetics/genetics] These observations of discrete inheritance and the segregation of alleles are collectively known as Mendel's first law or the Law of Segregation.
[src:genetics/genetics] However, the probability of getting one gene over the other can change due to dominant, recessive, homozygous, or heterozygous genes.
[src:genetics/genetics] For example, Mendel found that if you cross heterozygous organisms your odds of getting the dominant trait is 3:1.
[src:genetics/genetics] Real geneticist study and calculate probabilities by using theoretical probabilities, empirical probabilities, the product rule, the sum rule, and more.
[src:genetics/genetics] Geneticists use diagrams and symbols to describe inheritance.
[src:genetics/genetics] A gene is represented by one or a few letters.
[src:genetics/genetics] Often a "+" symbol is used to mark the usual, non-mutant allele for a gene.
[src:genetics/genetics] In fertilization and breeding experiments (and especially when discussing Mendel's laws) the parents are referred to as the "P" generation and the offspring as the "F1" (first filial) generation.
[src:genetics/genetics] When the F1 offspring mate with each other, the offspring are called the "F2" (second filial) generation.
[src:genetics/genetics] One of the common diagrams used to predict the result of cross-breeding is the Punnett square.
[src:genetics/genetics] When studying human genetic diseases, geneticists often use pedigree charts to represent the inheritance of traits.
[src:genetics/genetics] These charts map the inheritance of a trait in a family tree.
[src:genetics/genetics] Organisms have thousands of genes, and in sexually reproducing organisms these genes generally assort independently of each other.
[src:genetics/genetics] This means that the inheritance of an allele for yellow or green pea color is unrelated to the inheritance of alleles for white or purple flowers.
[src:genetics/genetics] This phenomenon, known as "Mendel's law of independent assortment, means that the alleles of different genes get shuffled between parents to form offspring with many different combinations.
[src:genetics/genetics] Different genes often interact to influence the same trait.
[src:genetics/genetics] In the Blue-eyed Mary (*Omphalodes verna*), for example, there exists a gene with alleles that determine the color of flowers: blue or magenta.
[src:genetics/genetics] Another gene, however, controls whether the flowers have color at all or are white.
[src:genetics/genetics] When a plant has two copies of this white allele, its flowers are white—regardless of whether the first gene has blue or magenta alleles.
[src:genetics/genetics] This interaction between genes is called epistasis, with the second gene epistatic to the first.
[src:genetics/genetics] Many traits are not discrete features (e.g. purple or white flowers) but are instead continuous features (e.g. human height and skin color).
[src:genetics/genetics] These complex traits are products of many genes.
[src:genetics/genetics] The influence of these genes is mediated, to varying degrees, by the environment an organism has experienced.
[src:genetics/genetics] The degree to which an organism's genes contribute to a complex trait is called heritability.
[src:genetics/genetics] Measurement of the heritability of a trait is relative—in a more variable environment, the environment has a bigger influence on the total variation of the trait.
[src:genetics/genetics] For example, human height is a trait with complex causes.
[src:genetics/genetics] It has a heritability of 89% in the United States.
[src:genetics/genetics] In Nigeria, however, where people experience a more variable access to good nutrition and health care, height has a heritability of only 62%.
[src:genetics/genetics] The molecular basis for genes is deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA).
[src:genetics/genetics] DNA is composed of deoxyribose (sugar molecule), a phosphate group, and a base (amine group).
[src:genetics/genetics] There are four types of bases: adenine (A), cytosine (C), guanine (G), and thymine (T).
[src:genetics/genetics] The phosphates make phosphodiester bonds with the sugars to make long phosphate-sugar backbones.
[src:genetics/genetics] Bases specifically pair together (T&A, C&G) between two backbones and make like rungs on a ladder.
[src:genetics/genetics] The bases, phosphates, and sugars together make a nucleotide that connects to make long chains of DNA.
[src:genetics/genetics] Genetic information exists in the sequence of these nucleotides, and genes exist as stretches of sequence along the DNA chain.
[src:genetics/genetics] These chains coil into a double a-helix structure and wrap around proteins called Histones which provide the structural support.
[src:genetics/genetics] DNA wrapped around these histones are called chromosomes.
[src:genetics/genetics] Viruses sometimes use the similar molecule RNA instead of DNA as their genetic material.
[src:genetics/genetics] DNA normally exists as a double-stranded molecule, coiled into the shape of a double helix.
[src:genetics/genetics] Each nucleotide in DNA preferentially pairs with its partner nucleotide on the opposite strand: A pairs with T, and C pairs with G.
[src:genetics/genetics] Thus, in its two-stranded form, each strand effectively contains all necessary information, redundant with its partner strand.
[src:genetics/genetics] This structure of DNA is the physical basis for inheritance: DNA replication duplicates the genetic information by splitting the strands and using each strand as a template for synthesis of a new partner strand.
[src:genetics/genetics] Genes are arranged linearly along long chains of DNA base-pair sequences.
[src:genetics/genetics] In bacteria, each cell usually contains a single circular genophore, while eukaryotic organisms (such as plants and animals) have their DNA arranged in multiple linear chromosomes.
[src:genetics/genetics] These DNA strands are often extremely long; the largest human chromosome, for example, is about 247 million base pairs in length.
[src:genetics/genetics] The DNA of a chromosome is associated with structural proteins that organize, compact, and control access to the DNA, forming a material called chromatin; in eukaryotes, chromatin is usually composed of nucleosomes, segments of DNA wound around cores of histone proteins.
[src:genetics/genetics] The full set of hereditary material in an organism (usually the combined DNA sequences of all chromosomes) is called the genome.
[src:genetics/genetics] DNA is most often found in the nucleus of cells, but Ruth Sager helped in the discovery of nonchromosomal genes found outside of the nucleus.
[src:genetics/genetics] In plants, these are often found in the chloroplasts and in other organisms, in the mitochondria.
[src:genetics/genetics] These nonchromosomal genes can still be passed on by either partner in sexual reproduction and they control a variety of hereditary characteristics that replicate and remain active throughout generations.
[src:genetics/genetics] While haploid organisms have only one copy of each chromosome, most animals and many plants are diploid, containing two of each chromosome and thus two copies of every gene.
[src:genetics/genetics] The two alleles for a gene are located on identical loci of the two homologous chromosomes, each allele inherited from a different parent.
[src:genetics/genetics] Many species have so-called sex chromosomes that determine the sex of each organism.
[src:genetics/genetics] In humans and many other animals, the Y chromosome contains the gene that triggers the development of the specifically male characteristics.
[src:genetics/genetics] In evolution, this chromosome has lost most of its content and also most of its genes, while the X chromosome is similar to the other chromosomes and contains many genes.
[src:genetics/genetics] This being said, Mary Frances Lyon discovered that there is X-chromosome inactivation during reproduction to avoid passing on twice as many genes to the offspring.
[src:genetics/genetics] Lyon's discovery led to the discovery of X-linked diseases.
[src:genetics/genetics] When cells divide, their full genome is copied and each daughter cell inherits one copy.
[src:genetics/genetics] This process, called mitosis, is the simplest form of reproduction and is the basis for asexual reproduction.
[src:genetics/genetics] Asexual reproduction can also occur in multicellular organisms, producing offspring that inherit their genome from a single parent.
[src:genetics/genetics] Offspring that are genetically identical to their parents are called clones.
[src:genetics/genetics] Eukaryotic organisms often use sexual reproduction to generate offspring that contain a mixture of genetic material inherited from two different parents.
[src:genetics/genetics] The process of sexual reproduction alternates between forms that contain single copies of the genome (haploid) and double copies (diploid).
[src:genetics/genetics] Haploid cells fuse and combine genetic material to create a diploid cell with paired chromosomes.
[src:genetics/genetics] Diploid organisms form haploids by dividing, without replicating their DNA, to create daughter cells that randomly inherit one of each pair of chromosomes.
[src:genetics/genetics] Most animals and many plants are diploid for most of their lifespan, with the haploid form reduced to single cell gametes such as sperm or eggs.
[src:genetics/genetics] Although they do not use the haploid/diploid method of sexual reproduction, bacteria have many methods of acquiring new genetic information.
[src:genetics/genetics] Some bacteria can undergo conjugation, transferring a small circular piece of DNA to another bacterium.
[src:genetics/genetics] Bacteria can also take up raw DNA fragments found in the environment and integrate them into their genomes, a phenomenon known as transformation.
[src:genetics/genetics] These processes result in horizontal gene transfer, transmitting fragments of genetic information between organisms that would be otherwise unrelated.
[src:genetics/genetics] Natural bacterial transformation occurs in many bacterial species, and can be regarded as a sexual process for transferring DNA from one cell to another cell (usually of the same species).
[src:genetics/genetics] Transformation requires the action of numerous bacterial gene products, and its primary adaptive function appears to be repair of DNA damages in the recipient cell.
[src:genetics/genetics] The diploid nature of chromosomes allows for genes on different chromosomes to assort independently or be separated from their homologous pair during sexual reproduction wherein haploid gametes are formed.
[src:genetics/genetics] In this way new combinations of genes can occur in the offspring of a mating pair.
[src:genetics/genetics] Genes on the same chromosome would theoretically never recombine.
[src:genetics/genetics] However, they do, via the cellular process of chromosomal crossover.
[src:genetics/genetics] During crossover, chromosomes exchange stretches of DNA, effectively shuffling the gene alleles between the chromosomes.
[src:genetics/genetics] This process of chromosomal crossover generally occurs during meiosis, a series of cell divisions that creates haploid cells.
[src:genetics/genetics] Meiotic recombination, particularly in microbial eukaryotes, appears to serve the adaptive function of repair of DNA damages.
[src:genetics/genetics] The first cytological demonstration of crossing over was performed by Harriet Creighton and Barbara McClintock in 1931.
[src:genetics/genetics] Their research and experiments on corn provided cytological evidence for the genetic theory that linked genes on paired chromosomes do in fact exchange places from one homolog to the other.
[src:genetics/genetics] The probability of chromosomal crossover occurring between two given points on the chromosome is related to the distance between the points.
[src:genetics/genetics] For an arbitrarily long distance, the probability of crossover is high enough that the inheritance of the genes is effectively uncorrelated.
[src:genetics/genetics] For genes that are closer together, however, the lower probability of crossover means that the genes demonstrate genetic linkage; alleles for the two genes tend to be inherited together.
[src:genetics/genetics] The amounts of linkage between a series of genes can be combined to form a linear linkage map that roughly describes the arrangement of the genes along the chromosome.
[src:genetics/genetics] Genes express their functional effect through the production of proteins, which are molecules responsible for most functions in the cell.
[src:genetics/genetics] Proteins are made up of one or more polypeptide chains, each composed of a sequence of amino acids.
[src:genetics/genetics] The DNA sequence of a gene is used to produce a specific amino acid sequence.
[src:genetics/genetics] This process begins with the production of an RNA molecule with a sequence matching the gene's DNA sequence, a process called transcription.
[src:genetics/genetics] This messenger RNA molecule then serves to produce a corresponding amino acid sequence through a process called translation.
[src:genetics/genetics] Each group of three nucleotides in the sequence, called a codon, corresponds either to one of the twenty possible amino acids in a protein or an instruction to end the amino acid sequence; this correspondence is called the genetic code.
[src:genetics/genetics] The flow of information is unidirectional: information is transferred from nucleotide sequences into the amino acid sequence of proteins, but it never transfers from protein back into the sequence of DNA—a phenomenon Francis Crick called the central dogma of molecular biology.
[src:genetics/genetics] The specific sequence of amino acids results in a unique three-dimensional structure for that protein, and the three-dimensional structures of proteins are related to their functions.
[src:genetics/genetics] Some are simple structural molecules, like the fibers formed by the protein collagen.
[src:genetics/genetics] Proteins can bind to other proteins and simple molecules, sometimes acting as enzymes by facilitating chemical reactions within the bound molecules (without changing the structure of the protein itself).
[src:genetics/genetics] Protein structure is dynamic; the protein hemoglobin bends into slightly different forms as it facilitates the capture, transport, and release of oxygen molecules within mammalian blood.
[src:genetics/genetics] A single nucleotide difference within DNA can cause a change in the amino acid sequence of a protein.
[src:genetics/genetics] Because protein structures are the result of their amino acid sequences, some changes can dramatically change the properties of a protein by destabilizing the structure or changing the surface of the protein in a way that changes its interaction with other proteins and molecules.
[src:genetics/genetics] For example, sickle-cell anemia is a human genetic disease that results from a single base difference within the coding region for the β-globin section of hemoglobin, causing a single amino acid change that changes hemoglobin's physical properties.
[src:genetics/genetics] Sickle-cell versions of hemoglobin stick to themselves, stacking to form fibers that distort the shape of red blood cells carrying the protein.
[src:genetics/genetics] These sickle-shaped cells no longer flow smoothly through blood vessels, having a tendency to clog or degrade, causing the medical problems associated with this disease.
[src:genetics/genetics] Some DNA sequences are transcribed into RNA but are not translated into protein products—such RNA molecules are called non-coding RNA.
[src:genetics/genetics] In some cases, these products fold into structures which are involved in critical cell functions (e.g. ribosomal RNA and transfer RNA).
[src:genetics/genetics] RNA can also have regulatory effects through hybridization interactions with other RNA molecules (such as microRNA).
[src:genetics/genetics] Although genes contain all the information an organism uses to function, the environment plays an important role in determining the ultimate phenotypes an organism displays.
[src:genetics/genetics] The phrase "nature and nurture" refers to this complementary relationship.
[src:genetics/genetics] The phenotype of an organism depends on the interaction of genes and the environment.
[src:genetics/genetics] An interesting example is the coat coloration of the Siamese cat.
[src:genetics/genetics] In this case, the body temperature of the cat plays the role of the environment.
[src:genetics/genetics] The cat's genes code for dark hair, thus the hair-producing cells in the cat make cellular proteins resulting in dark hair.
[src:genetics/genetics] But these dark hair-producing proteins are sensitive to temperature (i.e. have a mutation causing temperature-sensitivity) and denature in higher-temperature environments, failing to produce dark-hair pigment in areas where the cat has a higher body temperature.
[src:genetics/genetics] In a low-temperature environment, however, the protein's structure is stable and produces dark-hair pigment normally.
[src:genetics/genetics] The protein remains functional in areas of skin that are colder—such as its legs, ears, tail, and face—so the cat has dark hair at its extremities.
[src:genetics/genetics] Environment plays a major role in effects of the human genetic disease phenylketonuria.
[src:genetics/genetics] The mutation that causes phenylketonuria disrupts the ability of the body to break down the amino acid phenylalanine, causing a toxic build-up of an intermediate molecule that, in turn, causes severe symptoms of progressive intellectual disability and seizures.
[src:genetics/genetics] However, if someone with the phenylketonuria mutation follows a strict diet that avoids this amino acid, they remain normal and healthy.
[src:genetics/genetics] A common method for determining how genes and environment ("nature and nurture") contribute to a phenotype involves studying identical and fraternal twins, or other siblings of multiple births.
[src:genetics/genetics] Identical siblings are genetically the same since they come from the same zygote.
[src:genetics/genetics] Meanwhile, fraternal twins are as genetically different from one another as normal siblings.
[src:genetics/genetics] By comparing how often a certain disorder occurs in a pair of identical twins to how often it occurs in a pair of fraternal twins, scientists can determine whether that disorder is caused by genetic or postnatal environmental factors.
[src:genetics/genetics] One famous example involved the study of the Genain quadruplets, who were identical quadruplets all diagnosed with schizophrenia.
[src:genetics/genetics] The genome of a given organism contains thousands of genes, but not all these genes need to be active at any given moment.
[src:genetics/genetics] A gene is expressed when it is being transcribed into mRNA and there exist many cellular methods of controlling the expression of genes such that proteins are produced only when needed by the cell.
[src:genetics/genetics] Transcription factors are regulatory proteins that bind to DNA, either promoting or inhibiting the transcription of a gene.
[src:genetics/genetics] Within the genome of *Escherichia coli* bacteria, for example, there exists a series of genes necessary for the synthesis of the amino acid tryptophan.
[src:genetics/genetics] However, when tryptophan is already available to the cell, these genes for tryptophan synthesis are no longer needed.
[src:genetics/genetics] The presence of tryptophan directly affects the activity of the genes—tryptophan molecules bind to the tryptophan repressor (a transcription factor), changing the repressor's structure such that the repressor binds to the genes.
[src:genetics/genetics] The tryptophan repressor blocks the transcription and expression of the genes, thereby creating negative feedback regulation of the tryptophan synthesis process.
[src:genetics/genetics] Differences in gene expression are especially clear within multicellular organisms, where cells all contain the same genome but have very different structures and behaviors due to the expression of different sets of genes.
[src:genetics/genetics] All the cells in a multicellular organism derive from a single cell, differentiating into variant cell types in response to external and intercellular signals and gradually establishing different patterns of gene expression to create different behaviors.
[src:genetics/genetics] Within eukaryotes, there exist structural features of chromatin that influence the transcription of genes, often in the form of modifications to DNA and chromatin that are stably inherited by daughter cells.
[src:genetics/genetics] These features are called "epigenetic" because they exist "on top" of the DNA sequence and retain inheritance from one cell generation to the next.
[src:genetics/genetics] Because of epigenetic features, different cell types grown within the same medium can retain very different properties.
[src:genetics/genetics] Although epigenetic features are generally dynamic over the course of development, some, like the phenomenon of paramutation, have multigenerational inheritance and exist as rare exceptions to the general rule of DNA as the basis for inheritance.
[src:genetics/genetics] During the process of DNA replication, errors occasionally occur in the polymerization of the second strand.
[src:genetics/genetics] These errors, called mutations, can affect the phenotype of an organism, especially if they occur within the protein coding sequence of a gene.
[src:genetics/genetics] Error rates are usually very low—1 error in every 10–100 million bases—due to the "proofreading" ability of DNA polymerases.
[src:genetics/genetics] Processes that increase the rate of changes in DNA are called mutagenic: mutagenic chemicals promote errors in DNA replication, often by interfering with the structure of base-pairing, while UV radiation induces mutations by causing damage to the DNA structure.
[src:genetics/genetics] Chemical damage to DNA occurs naturally as well and cells use DNA repair mechanisms to repair mismatches and breaks.
[src:genetics/genetics] The repair does not, however, always restore the original sequence.
[src:genetics/genetics] A particularly important source of DNA damages appears to be reactive oxygen species produced by cellular aerobic respiration, and these can lead to mutations.
[src:genetics/genetics] In organisms that use chromosomal crossover to exchange DNA and recombine genes, errors in alignment during meiosis can also cause mutations.
[src:genetics/genetics] Errors in crossover are especially likely when similar sequences cause partner chromosomes to adopt a mistaken alignment; this makes some regions in genomes more prone to mutating in this way.
[src:genetics/genetics] These errors create large structural changes in DNA sequence—duplications, inversions, deletions of entire regions—or the accidental exchange of whole parts of sequences between different chromosomes, chromosomal translocation.
[src:genetics/genetics] Mutations alter an organism's genotype and occasionally this causes different phenotypes to appear.
[src:genetics/genetics] Most mutations have little effect on an organism's phenotype, health, or reproductive fitness.
[src:genetics/genetics] Mutations that do have an effect are usually detrimental, but occasionally some can be beneficial.
[src:genetics/genetics] Studies in the fly *Drosophila melanogaster* suggest that if a mutation changes a protein produced by a gene, about 70 percent of these mutations are harmful with the remainder being either neutral or weakly beneficial.
[src:genetics/genetics] Population genetics studies the distribution of genetic differences within populations and how these distributions change over time.
[src:genetics/genetics] Changes in the frequency of an allele in a population are mainly influenced by natural selection, where a given allele provides a selective or reproductive advantage to the organism, as well as other factors such as mutation, genetic drift, genetic hitchhiking, artificial selection and migration.
[src:genetics/genetics] Over many generations, the genomes of organisms can change significantly, resulting in evolution.
[src:genetics/genetics] In the process called adaptation, selection for beneficial mutations can cause a species to evolve into forms better able to survive in their environment.
[src:genetics/genetics] New species are formed through the process of speciation, often caused by geographical separations that prevent populations from exchanging genes with each other.
[src:genetics/genetics] By comparing the homology between different species' genomes, it is possible to calculate the evolutionary distance between them and when they may have diverged.
[src:genetics/genetics] Genetic comparisons are generally considered a more accurate method of characterizing the relatedness between species than the comparison of phenotypic characteristics.
[src:genetics/genetics] Although geneticists originally studied inheritance in a wide variety of organisms, the range of species studied has narrowed.
[src:genetics/genetics] One reason is that when significant research already exists for a given organism, new researchers are more likely to choose it for further study, and so eventually a few model organisms became the basis for most genetics research.
[src:genetics/genetics] Common research topics in model organism genetics include the study of gene regulation and the involvement of genes in development and cancer.
[src:genetics/genetics] Organisms were chosen, in part, for convenience—short generation times and easy genetic manipulation made some organisms popular genetics research tools.
[src:genetics/genetics] Medical genetics seeks to understand how genetic variation relates to human health and disease.
[src:genetics/genetics] When searching for an unknown gene that may be involved in a disease, researchers commonly use genetic linkage and genetic pedigree charts to find the location on the genome associated with the disease.
[src:genetics/genetics] At the population level, researchers take advantage of genome wide association studies (GWAS) to look for locations in the genome that are associated with diseases, a method especially useful for multigenic traits not clearly defined by a single gene.
[src:genetics/genetics] Once a candidate gene is found, further research is often done on the corresponding (or homologous) genes of model organisms.
[src:genetics/genetics] In addition to studying genetic diseases, the increased availability of genotyping methods has led to the field of pharmacogenetics: the study of how genotype can affect drug responses.
[src:genetics/genetics] Individuals differ in their inherited tendency to develop cancer, and cancer is a genetic disease.
[src:genetics/genetics] The process of cancer development in the body is a combination of events.
[src:genetics/genetics] Mutations occasionally occur within cells in the body as they divide.
[src:genetics/genetics] Although these mutations will not be inherited by any offspring, they can affect the behavior of cells, sometimes causing them to grow and divide more frequently.
[src:genetics/genetics] There are biological mechanisms that attempt to stop this process; signals are given to inappropriately dividing cells that should trigger cell death, but sometimes additional mutations occur that cause cells to ignore these messages.
[src:genetics/genetics] An internal process of natural selection occurs within the body and eventually mutations accumulate within cells to promote their own growth, creating a cancerous tumor that grows and invades various tissues of the body.
[src:genetics/genetics] Normally, a cell divides only in response to signals called growth factors and stops growing once in contact with surrounding cells and in response to growth-inhibitory signals.
[src:genetics/genetics] It usually then divides a limited number of times and dies, staying within the epithelium where it is unable to migrate to other organs.
[src:genetics/genetics] To become a cancer cell, a cell has to accumulate mutations in a number of genes (three to seven).
[src:genetics/genetics] A cancer cell can divide without growth factor and ignores inhibitory signals.
[src:genetics/genetics] Also, it is immortal and can grow indefinitely, even after it makes contact with neighboring cells.
[src:genetics/genetics] It may escape from the epithelium and ultimately from the primary tumor.
[src:genetics/genetics] Then, the escaped cell can cross the endothelium of a blood vessel and get transported by the bloodstream to colonize a new organ, forming deadly metastasis.
[src:genetics/genetics] The most frequent mutations are a loss of function of p53 protein, a tumor suppressor, or in the p53 pathway, and gain of function mutations in the Ras proteins, or in other oncogenes.
[src:genetics/genetics] DNA can be manipulated in the laboratory.
[src:genetics/genetics] Restriction enzymes are commonly used enzymes that cut DNA at specific sequences, producing predictable fragments of DNA.
[src:genetics/genetics] DNA fragments can be visualized through use of gel electrophoresis, which separates fragments according to their length.
[src:genetics/genetics] The use of ligation enzymes allows DNA fragments to be connected.
[src:genetics/genetics] By binding ("ligating") fragments of DNA together from different sources, researchers can create recombinant DNA, the DNA often associated with genetically modified organisms.
[src:genetics/genetics] Recombinant DNA is commonly used in the context of plasmids: short circular DNA molecules with a few genes on them.
[src:genetics/genetics] In the process known as molecular cloning, researchers can amplify the DNA fragments by inserting plasmids into bacteria and then culturing them on plates of agar (to isolate clones of bacteria cells).
[src:genetics/genetics] "Cloning" can also refer to the various means of creating cloned ("clonal") organisms.
[src:genetics/genetics] DNA can also be amplified using a procedure called the polymerase chain reaction (PCR).
[src:genetics/genetics] By using specific short sequences of DNA, PCR can isolate and exponentially amplify a targeted region of DNA.
[src:genetics/genetics] Because it can amplify from extremely small amounts of DNA, PCR is also often used to detect the presence of specific DNA sequences.
[src:genetics/genetics] DNA sequencing, one of the most fundamental technologies developed to study genetics, allows researchers to determine the sequence of nucleotides in DNA fragments.
[src:genetics/genetics] The technique of chain-termination sequencing, developed in 1977 by a team led by Frederick Sanger, is still routinely used to sequence DNA fragments.
[src:genetics/genetics] Using this technology, researchers have been able to study the molecular sequences associated with many human diseases.
[src:genetics/genetics] As sequencing has become less expensive, researchers have sequenced the genomes of many organisms using a process called genome assembly, which uses computational tools to stitch together sequences from many different fragments.
[src:genetics/genetics] These technologies were used to sequence the human genome in the Human Genome Project completed in 2003.
[src:genetics/genetics] New high-throughput sequencing technologies are dramatically lowering the cost of DNA sequencing, with many researchers hoping to bring the cost of resequencing a human genome down to a thousand dollars.
[src:genetics/genetics] Next-generation sequencing (or high-throughput sequencing) came about due to the ever-increasing demand for low-cost sequencing.
[src:genetics/genetics] These sequencing technologies allow the production of potentially millions of sequences concurrently.
[src:genetics/genetics] The large amount of sequence data available has created the subfield of genomics, research that uses computational tools to search for and analyze patterns in the full genomes of organisms.
[src:genetics/genetics] Genomics can also be considered a subfield of bioinformatics, which uses computational approaches to analyze large sets of biological data.
[src:genetics/genetics] On 19 March 2015, a group of leading biologists urged a worldwide ban on clinical use of methods, particularly the use of CRISPR and zinc finger, to edit the human genome in a way that can be inherited.
[src:genetics/genetics] In April 2015, Chinese researchers reported results of basic research to edit the DNA of non-viable human embryos using CRISPR.
